-- ============================================================
-- Batch 20: 25 curated AI tools (Step 41 — scale to 1,500)
-- Hand-authored enrichment via parallel research. Every tool satisfies
-- ≥3/5 plan §41 criteria: trending, growing, in-use, category-gap-filler,
-- not-a-wrapper. All slugs deduped vs the existing 1,040-tool catalog.
-- All website_url values are bare canonical domains — no UTM, no ref,
-- no affiliate redirector. Affiliate program metadata tracked separately
-- in RightAIChoice_Affiliate_Master.xlsx.
-- ============================================================

INSERT INTO tools (
  name, slug, tagline, description, website_url,
  pricing_type, pricing_details, skill_level, has_api, platforms,
  features, integrations, is_published,
  best_for, not_for, editorial_verdict,
  tutorial_urls, limitations, models, community_links, use_cases, our_views,
  last_verified_at
) VALUES
('Surfer SEO', 'surfer-seo', 'On-page SEO content optimisation platform that scores drafts against live SERP competitors.', 'Surfer SEO is a browser-based content optimisation tool that analyses the top-ranking pages for any target keyword and produces a Content Editor with a real-time score, recommended word count, heading structure, NLP-derived terms to include, and internal-link suggestions. Writers paste or draft inside the editor and watch the score climb as they hit the brief, which makes the abstract task of "writing for SEO" concrete enough for non-specialists to execute.

Around the editor sit a handful of complementary modules: a Topical Map planner that proposes article clusters, an AI Outline generator, an Auto-Optimize feature that rewrites existing pages against the live SERP, an Audit tool that benchmarks a published URL against ranking competitors, and an SEO Surfer Writer that drafts whole articles end-to-end using the same SERP-aware brief. The integrations with Google Docs, WordPress, Jasper, and Contentful let editorial teams keep their existing workflow.

Surfer''s niche in 2026 is clear: it is the competitor-data layer between keyword research (Ahrefs / Semrush) and writing (Google Docs / a generative writer). Teams use it to brief freelancers, score drafts before publishing, and audit underperforming posts. It is one of the most widely-adopted on-page tools in the SEO industry — the Content Editor score has effectively become a standard format for SEO content briefs.', 'https://surferseo.com', 'paid', '[{"plan":"Essential","price":"$99/mo","features":["30 Content Editor articles/mo","Topical Maps","AI Outline","Audit"]},{"plan":"Scale","price":"$219/mo","features":["100 articles/mo","Auto-Optimize","White-label PDFs","Multiple workspaces"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"Custom","features":["Custom limits","SSO","API access","Priority support"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"Content Editor with real-time SERP-based score","NLP term suggestions and density targets","Topical Map cluster planner","AI Outline generator","Auto-Optimize for existing URLs","SERP Audit tool with competitor diff","SEO Surfer Writer (full-draft generator)","Google Docs and WordPress plugins","Internal linking suggestions","Multi-language support (10+ languages)"}', '{"Google Docs","WordPress","Jasper","Contentful","SEMrush","Surfer API","Zapier"}', true, '{"Content marketers briefing freelancers against a SERP","In-house SEO teams scoring drafts before publishing","Agencies running on-page audits at scale","Bloggers optimising for high-intent commercial keywords"}', '{"Brand / thought-leadership writers who don''t want to write to a template","Teams without a real keyword pipeline (no input means no value)","News publishers (SERP shifts too fast for the score to be useful)"}', 'The default on-page SEO scoring tool in 2026 — pick it if your writers need a concrete brief and a score to hit, skip it if your content is brand-led rather than search-led.', '{"https://docs.surferseo.com/"}', 'The score is a guide, not a guarantee — hitting 80+ does not mean you''ll rank if backlinks, intent match, or domain authority are weak. NLP suggestions skew toward keyword stuffing if writers chase the score blindly, which can produce stilted prose. Pricing jumps steeply between tiers — the Essential plan''s 30-article limit is tight for any real content team. The AI Writer output is acceptable for templated commercial pages but thin on genuine insight.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Score a 2,000-word commercial blog post against the top 10 ranking pages before publishing.","Audit a year-old article that lost rankings and get a prioritised list of fixes.","Generate an SEO brief (outline, terms, word count) to send to a freelance writer.","Plan a 30-article topical cluster around a pillar page using the Topical Map module."}', 'Sweet spot: a content team that produces commercial / informational SEO articles weekly and needs a shared standard for "is this draft ready to publish?" The Content Editor score is the brief, the QA gate, and the freelance feedback mechanism in one — which collapses three internal documents into one tool.

Failure modes to know. First, Goodhart''s Law applies — once writers optimise for the score, prose quality drops. Mitigate by treating the score as a floor (hit 70+, then edit for human readability) rather than a ceiling. Second, Surfer alone won''t rank you — if your domain authority is weak or your backlink profile is thin, no on-page score fixes that. Third, the AI Writer is a productivity feature, not a quality one; humans still need to fact-check and rewrite the output.

What to pilot before committing. Take your last 10 published articles. Run them through Surfer''s Audit and Auto-Optimize features, ship the suggested fixes, and track ranking movement over 60 days. If at least 4 of 10 move up materially, the tool earns its seat. If fewer move, your bottleneck is upstream (keyword targeting, backlinks, intent) and Surfer won''t solve it.', now()),
('NeuronWriter', 'neuronwriter', 'Semantic-SEO content editor with deep SERP analysis at a fraction of Surfer''s price.', 'NeuronWriter is a content optimisation platform built by Polish team CONTADU that pitches itself directly against Surfer SEO on price and depth of SERP analysis. The core flow is identical — paste a target keyword, get a live brief with score, terms, heading structure, and competitor diff — but NeuronWriter goes deeper on entity / topic modelling, includes search-intent classification, and bundles plagiarism + AI-detection checks into the editor.

The product covers the full content cycle: keyword discovery, competitor SERP analysis, AI-assisted drafting (GPT-4-class output via your own API key or built-in credits), the Content Editor itself, internal-link suggestions across your indexed site, and a publishing pipeline to WordPress / Shopify. Workspaces are per-domain rather than per-seat, which makes it noticeably cheaper for agencies running many client sites in parallel.

NeuronWriter became a popular Surfer alternative through aggressive AppSumo lifetime deals in 2022–2024, and the product has matured significantly since — the 2026 version is a fully credible alternative for most use cases, particularly for solo SEOs and small agencies who can''t justify Surfer''s subscription tier.', 'https://neuronwriter.com', 'paid', '[{"plan":"Bronze","price":"$23/mo","features":["25 content analyses/mo","2 projects","AI writing 15K credits"]},{"plan":"Silver","price":"$45/mo","features":["50 analyses/mo","5 projects","Plagiarism check","Internal linking"]},{"plan":"Gold","price":"$69/mo","features":["75 analyses/mo","10 projects","White-label PDFs","API access"]},{"plan":"Platinum","price":"$93/mo","features":["100 analyses/mo","25 projects","Priority support"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"Content Editor with semantic-SEO score","Entity and topic modelling beyond raw keywords","Search-intent classification per query","Built-in AI writing (GPT-4-class) with credits","Plagiarism and AI-content detection","Internal link suggester across indexed pages","Competitor SERP and outline scraper","WordPress and Shopify publishing","Per-domain workspaces (agency-friendly pricing)","Multi-language support (170+ languages)"}', '{"WordPress","Shopify","Google Search Console","OpenAI","Zapier","Make"}', true, '{"Solo SEOs and freelancers who can''t justify Surfer pricing","Small agencies managing 5-25 client sites","Affiliate marketers running multiple niche sites","International SEO teams (170+ language coverage)"}', '{"Enterprise teams needing audit logs and SSO","Brand writers who don''t care about SERP-based briefs","Teams already locked into Clearscope / MarketMuse workflows"}', 'A genuine Surfer alternative at roughly a third of the price, with deeper entity modelling. The pricing per project / domain is what makes it unbeatable for agencies.', '{"https://docs.neuronwriter.com/"}', 'The UI is denser and less polished than Surfer — expect a steeper first-week learning curve. Built-in AI writing credits are limited; serious drafting still wants you to plug in your own OpenAI key. Some long-tail languages have thinner SERP datasets, which can make scores noisy. Customer support is email-only and slower than Surfer''s live chat.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Optimise 50 product-category pages across 5 client sites without 5x Surfer subscriptions.","Brief a freelance writer with a semantic-SEO score and entity list to hit.","Run plagiarism + AI detection on guest posts before publishing.","Build an internal-linking map across an indexed 500-page site."}', 'Sweet spot: a solo SEO or small agency that has tried Surfer, agreed it works, but balks at $99–$219/month per seat. NeuronWriter delivers the same core workflow — SERP brief, score-driven editing, internal links — at $45–$69/month with per-domain limits that scale better for multi-client work.

Failure modes. The UI density is real — onboarding a new team member takes longer than with Surfer''s cleaner interface. Built-in AI credits run out fast on heavy drafting weeks; budget for an OpenAI API key on top. The brand still carries lifetime-deal stigma in some SEO circles, which can be an issue if you''re selling content services to enterprise buyers who only know Surfer / Clearscope.

What to pilot. Pick a single client domain. Run the same five articles through NeuronWriter that you''d normally run through Surfer. Compare the briefs, the recommended terms, and the resulting rankings 60 days post-publish. If outcomes are within 10% of Surfer''s, the price gap makes the switch obvious. If NeuronWriter''s briefs miss material terms, stay on Surfer for that workflow but consider NeuronWriter for secondary sites.', now()),
('Paperpal', 'paperpal', 'AI academic writing assistant from Cactus / Editage built specifically for researchers and PhD students.', 'Paperpal is an academic-writing AI tool from Cactus Communications, the same company behind the Editage editing service used by hundreds of thousands of researchers worldwide. Unlike general-purpose writers (Grammarly, ChatGPT), Paperpal is trained specifically on academic English: it suggests discipline-appropriate phrasing, catches non-native-speaker errors common in research papers, checks technical compliance with journal-style requirements, and offers paraphrasing that preserves citations and technical terminology.

The product comes in several surfaces: a web editor, a Microsoft Word add-in (used by most academic writers in their normal flow), a browser extension, and integrations with Overleaf for LaTeX users. Beyond grammar, Paperpal includes pre-submission checks (journal selection, plagiarism, AI-content disclosure scan, language polishing), a Research Assistant for literature search across millions of papers, and a Manuscript Translator optimised for academic registers.

Paperpal''s authority comes from its parent: Cactus / Editage has been the dominant academic editing brand for two decades, and the AI features were trained on the firm''s editorial style guides and historical edits. For non-native English researchers preparing manuscripts for international journals, Paperpal''s suggestions reflect what a human Editage editor would change — which is precisely the value.', 'https://paperpal.com', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["Limited language suggestions","Basic paraphrasing","Web editor"]},{"plan":"Prime","price":"$19/mo or $99/yr","features":["Unlimited language suggestions","Word add-in","Pre-submission checks","Research Assistant"]},{"plan":"Institutional","price":"Custom","features":["Bulk seats","SSO","Compliance reporting","Branded portal"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","desktop"}', '{"Microsoft Word add-in (primary surface for most users)","Academic-English language suggestions","Paraphrasing that preserves citations and technical terms","Plagiarism checker with similarity report","AI-content detection and disclosure helper","Pre-submission journal-style checks","Research Assistant — literature search across millions of papers","Manuscript translator (25+ languages)","Browser extension","Overleaf / LaTeX integration"}', '{"Microsoft Word","Overleaf","Google Docs","Editage editing services","ResearchGate","Zotero"}', true, '{"Non-native English researchers preparing manuscripts for international journals","PhD students writing dissertations under time pressure","Postdocs revising rejected papers for resubmission","University writing centres supporting graduate students"}', '{"Marketers / business writers (general tools fit better)","Fiction or creative writers (the academic register hurts here)","Researchers who only need Grammarly-level grammar checks (overkill)"}', 'The strongest AI writing tool built specifically for academic English in 2026 — pick it if you publish in journals, skip it if you write blogs.', '{"https://paperpal.com/help"}', 'Coverage is strongest in life sciences, medicine, and engineering — humanities and pure-mathematics writing get less specialised support. The Research Assistant''s database is good but smaller than Scopus or Web of Science — treat it as a starting point, not a comprehensive lit review. Plagiarism similarity scores aren''t identical to Turnitin''s — if your university uses Turnitin for grading, Paperpal''s number is indicative only. Free tier is too limited for serious work.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Polish a manuscript draft inside Microsoft Word before submitting to a target journal.","Run a pre-submission check (language, references, plagiarism, AI-content) in 10 minutes.","Translate a Chinese-language draft into publication-ready academic English.","Find 20 cite-worthy related papers for a literature review section."}', 'Sweet spot: a non-native English researcher — typical user is a postdoc or PhD student in China, India, Brazil, or continental Europe — who is writing for an international journal and needs the manuscript to read like a native English academic wrote it. Paperpal''s suggestions reflect actual Editage editorial standards, which is a meaningfully different thing from Grammarly''s general-English corrections.

Failure modes. The pre-submission checks can give a false sense of safety: passing Paperpal''s plagiarism check doesn''t guarantee passing the journal''s Turnitin scan, and the AI-content detector is best-effort. Editorial domain coverage is uneven — a chemistry paper gets stronger suggestions than a Renaissance literature paper. The Research Assistant is convenient but not exhaustive, and shouldn''t replace a proper Scopus / Web of Science search.

What to pilot. Run your last submitted manuscript (one you''ve already had peer-reviewed) through Paperpal''s Word add-in. Compare its suggestions to the actual reviewer comments and the language edits you accepted. If the overlap is meaningful — Paperpal flagged things reviewers also flagged — it earns its annual subscription. If it mostly suggests trivial grammar fixes Grammarly already catches, you don''t need it.', now()),
('Rytr', 'rytr', 'Affordable general-purpose AI writer with 40+ use-case templates aimed at solopreneurs.', 'Rytr is a long-running AI writing tool that has stayed deliberately simple: pick a use case from a list of 40+ templates (blog post, product description, email, ad copy, song lyrics, cover letter), provide a short brief, and the model produces a draft in seconds. Outputs are competent rather than spectacular, but the workflow is fast, and the price point — including a usable free tier and a $9/month Unlimited plan — is the lowest in the AI-writing-tool category.

The product offers a clean editor, a built-in plagiarism checker, a Chrome extension, browser-based image generation, a tone-of-voice picker (30+ tones), 30+ output languages, and an SEO module that generates keyword-aware briefs. Team plans add seats and shared assets. There is no SERP-based competitor analysis (Surfer / NeuronWriter territory), no agentic browsing, and no advanced workflow automation — Rytr is unapologetically a general-purpose drafting assistant.

Rytr''s position in 2026 is the value tier. It is rarely the first choice for serious content teams (Jasper, Writesonic, or direct GPT-4 access do more), but it is the right pick for the long tail of solopreneurs, side-hustle marketers, and freelancers who write at moderate volume and care more about predictable monthly cost than about cutting-edge features.', 'https://rytr.me', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["10K characters/mo","40+ use cases","Plagiarism check (limited)"]},{"plan":"Unlimited","price":"$9/mo","features":["Unlimited generations","All use cases","Premium community","Chrome extension"]},{"plan":"Premium","price":"$29/mo","features":["Unlimited","Priority chat support","Custom use case","API access"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"40+ use-case templates (blog, email, ad, social, etc)","30+ tones of voice","30+ output languages","Built-in plagiarism checker","SEO mode with keyword-aware drafts","Browser-based AI image generation","Chrome extension","Team workspaces (Premium tier)","API access","Document editor with format export"}', '{"WordPress","Shopify","Chrome","Zapier","API","Slack (via Zapier)"}', true, '{"Solopreneurs writing blog and email content weekly","Freelancers producing volume copy on a tight margin","Side-hustle marketers who need cheap, fast drafts","Non-English-first writers wanting decent multilingual output"}', '{"Enterprise content teams needing brand-voice consistency at scale","SEO teams that want SERP-based briefs (use Surfer / NeuronWriter)","Researchers / academics (use Paperpal)"}', 'The cheapest credible general-purpose AI writer in 2026. Output quality is "good enough" rather than premium — pick it on price, not on quality.', '{"https://rytr.me/help"}', 'Output quality is below GPT-4-class direct access — you''ll often regenerate twice or rewrite chunks. The plagiarism checker is built on a smaller index than Copyscape and shouldn''t be the only check before publishing. Brand-voice features are thinner than Jasper or Writer — Rytr has 30+ tones but no real persistent brand voice training. The free tier''s 10K-character cap is hit quickly during real work.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Generate 20 product descriptions for a Shopify catalogue in under an hour.","Draft a weekly newsletter''s first pass before human editing.","Produce ad-copy variants (Facebook, Google, LinkedIn) for a small-business campaign.","Write a multilingual welcome email sequence in Spanish, French, and Portuguese."}', 'Sweet spot: a one-person content operation — freelancer, solopreneur, side-hustle marketer — who writes 5–20 pieces per week, needs the unit economics to work, and is fine with "competent first draft" rather than "ready to publish." At $9/month, Rytr pays for itself if it saves you 30 minutes a week.

Failure modes. The most common mistake is using Rytr where you need a more capable writer. If you''re producing flagship blog content, customer-facing thought leadership, or anything that competes on quality with hand-written work, Rytr''s output ceiling will frustrate you quickly. The other failure mode: assuming the plagiarism checker is sufficient — it isn''t at scale.

What to pilot. Try the free tier on your three most common writing tasks (whatever they are — emails, product copy, blog intros). Time how long the full Rytr-draft → human-edit cycle takes versus your current workflow. If you save 25%+ on time at acceptable quality, the $9 plan is a no-brainer. If you find yourself rewriting more than half the output, your tasks need a stronger model and Rytr will frustrate you.', now()),
('Lex', 'lex', 'Collaborative AI-native word processor that feels like Google Docs with a writing partner built in.', 'Lex is a browser-based word processor built from the ground up around AI assistance. The interface is deliberately minimal — a clean page that looks closer to Medium than to Word — but the AI is woven throughout: select any sentence and ask for a critique, hit a keyboard shortcut to have the model continue your draft, ask questions about your own text in a chat sidebar, or invoke "Ask Lex" inline to get suggestions without breaking flow. Documents are real-time collaborative, with cursors, comments, and tracked changes like Google Docs.

The model layer supports GPT-4-class outputs from OpenAI and Claude from Anthropic, switchable per-document. Lex defaults toward thoughtful writing rather than templated output — features like "Critique" that argues against your draft, "What''s missing?" that flags gaps in reasoning, and "Suggest counterarguments" that challenges your assertions are positioned for essayists, journalists, and serious non-fiction writers rather than for marketers cranking out blog posts.

Lex was founded by a small team out of a journalism / publishing background, and the product''s opinions show: it does not lean into "1-click viral content" or SEO-score features. It is a quietly different bet — that the right assist for serious writers is not "write this for me" but "make this draft better."', 'https://lex.page', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["Unlimited documents","GPT-4 access","Real-time collaboration","Critique and Ask Lex"]},{"plan":"Pro","price":"$15/mo","features":["Higher message limits","Claude access","Priority model speed","Advanced formatting"]},{"plan":"Teams","price":"Custom","features":["Shared workspaces","SSO","Admin controls","Volume model usage"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', false, '{"web"}', '{"Clean Medium-style writing surface","Inline AI suggestions and continuations","Critique mode (model argues against your draft)","\"What''s missing?\" gap analysis","Counterargument generator","Real-time collaborative editing with comments","Switchable models (GPT-4-class and Claude)","Document-aware chat sidebar","Markdown export and import","Track changes and version history"}', '{"OpenAI","Anthropic","Markdown","Google Drive (export)","Substack (export)"}', true, '{"Essayists and journalists drafting long-form pieces","Non-fiction authors working through book chapters","Founders writing memos, investor updates, and thought leadership","Academics drafting commentary or popular-press articles"}', '{"Marketers writing SEO blog content (no SERP features, no template library)","Teams needing Word-equivalent formatting (Lex stays minimal by design)","Anyone who wants the AI to write the whole draft in one click"}', 'The most opinionated and least gimmicky AI writing tool in 2026 — pick it if you take writing seriously and want a thoughtful collaborator, not a content-generation engine.', '{"https://lex.page/about"}', 'No native mobile app — it''s a web-only product, and writing on phones is awkward. Formatting is intentionally minimal: no tables, no advanced page layout, no native footnotes for academic styles (Word / Overleaf still win there). Free-tier model usage is generous but not infinite — heavy users will hit Pro pricing. No built-in plagiarism, SEO, or brand-voice features — by design, but it means Lex is a complement to, not a replacement for, those tools.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Draft a 2,000-word essay and use Critique mode to stress-test the argument before publishing.","Write a Substack post collaboratively with a co-author, with both cursors live in the same document.","Use \"What''s missing?\" to find logical gaps in an investor memo before sending.","Pull together a long-form journalism piece with model-generated counterarguments to interview sources."}', 'Sweet spot: a serious non-fiction writer — essayist, journalist, founder, academic doing public-facing writing — who values the editing process and finds most AI writers either too templated (Jasper, Rytr) or too neutral (raw ChatGPT). Lex''s personality is "thoughtful editor sitting next to you," and writers who want that energy fall in love with it; writers who want a content engine bounce off it.

Failure modes. If your job is producing volume — 20 SEO articles a week, a content-marketing pipeline, e-commerce product copy — Lex is the wrong tool and you will fight its opinions. The minimal formatting also bites if your output destination is Word with tracked changes for an editor, or Overleaf with proper academic citations. And the lack of a mobile app is a real friction for writers who draft on the go.

What to pilot. Move one piece — a single essay, memo, or article — entirely into Lex from blank page to publish. Use Critique, Ask Lex, and the gap-analysis features actively, not passively. If at the end you feel the draft is sharper than your normal process produces, the tool is doing real work. If the AI features felt ignorable, your existing workflow is fine and Lex is a luxury.', now()),
('Magnific AI', 'magnific-ai', 'AI image upscaler and enhancer that hallucinates believable detail, now part of Freepik.', 'Magnific AI is an upscaler and image enhancer built by Javi Lopez and Emilio Nicolas that became famous in early 2024 for producing upscales that did not just sharpen pixels — they invented plausible new detail at the requested resolution. A blurry character portrait could come back with realistic hair strands, fabric weave, and skin texture. Two sliders — Creativity and HDR — let you trade off fidelity vs. invention.

In May 2024, Magnific was acquired by Freepik, the Spanish stock-imagery giant. The standalone product still operates at magnific.ai with its original UI and pricing, and the same engine has been folded into Freepik''s broader AI suite. Treat Magnific as a current, actively-developed product — not a sunset one — but expect feature roadmap to align with Freepik''s priorities going forward.

The tool sits in a specific creative niche: photographers cleaning up portrait shoots, concept artists rescuing low-res references, e-commerce teams enhancing product photos, and AI-image users finishing Midjourney / SDXL outputs at print resolution. It is not a general image editor, and at its higher Creativity settings it will redraw faces and hands in ways that diverge from the source — that is the feature, not a bug.', 'https://magnific.ai', 'paid', '[{"plan":"Pro","price":"$39/mo","features":["3,000 credits/mo","Up to 16K upscales","Standard queue"]},{"plan":"Premium","price":"$99/mo","features":["10,000 credits/mo","Priority queue","Commercial license"]},{"plan":"Business","price":"$199/mo","features":["27,000 credits/mo","Top priority","Team features"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', false, '{"web"}', '{"AI upscaling up to 16K resolution","Creativity slider for detail invention","HDR slider for tonal range expansion","Resemblance control to stay close to source","Style transfer presets","Magnific Relight (relighting any image)","Magnific Structure (control composition)","Batch processing","Commercial license on paid tiers","Freepik integration"}', '{"Freepik","Photoshop (via export)","Midjourney (downstream)","Stable Diffusion (downstream)"}', true, '{"Photographers enhancing portrait and product shots","Concept artists upscaling low-res references","Midjourney users finishing images at print resolution","E-commerce teams sharpening product imagery"}', '{"Users needing pixel-faithful upscaling (Magnific reinvents detail)","Free or budget users (no free tier)","Bulk-volume workflows where credit math gets expensive"}', 'The most creative AI upscaler on the market — invents detail other tools can''t. Best for finishing artistic work, not for archival fidelity.', '{"https://magnific.ai/tutorials"}', 'No free tier and entry pricing starts at $39/mo — it''s a tool you commit to, not try casually. Higher Creativity settings will redraw faces, hands, and small text in ways that diverge from the source — useless for ID photos or document scanning. Acquired by Freepik in May 2024, so long-term roadmap is now tied to Freepik''s strategy, not the original founders''. Credit math can get expensive on 16K outputs.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Upscale a Midjourney portrait to 8K for a print campaign with believable skin and hair detail.","Rescue a 1080p product photo for an e-commerce hero image at 4K.","Relight a flat studio shot to look like golden-hour photography using Magnific Relight.","Sharpen and enhance a concept-art reference before sending to a finishing artist."}', 'Sweet spot: a creative professional who already pays for Midjourney or shoots photography and needs a finishing step that does more than nearest-neighbour upscaling. Magnific''s detail-invention is genuinely best-in-class — competitors like Topaz and Upscayl focus on faithful enlargement; Magnific is willing to make creative choices, and for artistic output that is what you want.

Failure modes. The same creativity that makes Magnific great makes it dangerous for any use case that requires fidelity — IDs, documents, evidence photos, anything legal or scientific. The price point excludes hobbyists, and credits burn fast on max-resolution jobs. Post-Freepik acquisition, the standalone product still works exactly as before, but a non-zero chance the roadmap consolidates into Freepik''s suite over time means treat it as a productivity tool you''re renting, not a moat.

What to pilot. Run 10 real images through Magnific at three Creativity settings (low, medium, high). Pick the setting that matches your tolerance for invention. If 8 of 10 outputs save you meaningful retouching work, the $39/mo tier pays for itself within a month; if you find yourself fighting hallucinated details, a faithful upscaler like Topaz Gigapixel will fit your workflow better.', now()),
('Recraft', 'recraft', 'AI image generator with native vector output and brand-style consistency for designers.', 'Recraft is an image-generation platform that treats designers as the primary user, not prompters. Where most AI image tools optimise for photorealistic raster output, Recraft natively generates vector graphics (SVG), maintains brand styles across batches, and gives precise control over typography, layout, and color palettes. The V4 model — its current generation — produces icons, illustrations, infographics, and product mockups that drop straight into Figma without manual tracing.

The platform pairs the model with workflow features designers actually need: a "style" feature where you can train the model on your brand''s visual language and reuse it across hundreds of generations, image-to-vector conversion, AI-powered background removal, and a Recraft API for integrating into design pipelines or apps.

It is one of the few image generators built explicitly for production design work rather than social-media art. The free tier is generous enough for evaluation; paid tiers unlock commercial licensing, larger generations, and API access. Adoption inside design teams at startups and agencies has grown sharply through 2025.', 'https://www.recraft.ai', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["50 daily credits","Personal use","Community styles"]},{"plan":"Basic","price":"$10/mo","features":["1,000 credits/mo","Commercial license","Custom styles"]},{"plan":"Advanced","price":"$33/mo","features":["3,000 credits/mo","Vector exports","Higher resolution"]},{"plan":"Pro","price":"$60/mo","features":["7,000 credits/mo","API access","Priority generation"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"Native SVG vector generation","V4 model for raster and vector output","Brand style training and reuse","Image-to-vector conversion","Background removal","Mockup and infographic templates","Color palette control","Typography-aware layouts","API for pipeline integration","Commercial license on paid tiers"}', '{"Figma (via SVG export)","Adobe Illustrator (via SVG)","Canva (via export)","Webflow (via SVG)"}', true, '{"Designers needing vector-ready icons and illustrations","Brand teams enforcing visual consistency across generations","Agencies producing client deliverables at scale","Developers integrating image generation into design tools"}', '{"Photorealistic portrait generation (Midjourney is stronger)","Users who only need raster art (cheaper alternatives exist)","One-off prompters (Recraft''s value is workflow, not single images)"}', 'The first AI image tool built for designers, not prompters. Native SVG output and brand styles are the features that close the gap to real production work.', '{"https://www.recraft.ai/docs"}', 'Photorealism is not Recraft''s strength — for portraits and product photos, Midjourney or Flux outperform. Vector quality on complex illustrations sometimes still needs cleanup in Illustrator. Style training requires 10+ reference images and tuning to get a consistent brand match. The free tier is good for evaluation but commercial use requires a paid tier.', '{"recraft-v4"}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Generate a 30-icon set in your brand''s exact style for a marketing site.","Produce vector illustrations for a SaaS landing page that drop straight into Figma.","Create a custom style from 15 reference designs and reuse it across a quarter of campaigns.","Build a programmatic image-generation pipeline using the API for a design tool product."}', 'Sweet spot: an in-house designer or small agency producing vector assets — icons, illustrations, infographics — at volume for product or marketing work. Recraft compresses the "generate, edit in Illustrator, fix the SVG" loop into a single tool. Brand-style training is the genuine moat: once you''ve set up your style, every subsequent generation feels like it came from the same designer.

Failure modes. If your work is photorealistic — portraits, product photography, lifestyle shots — Recraft is the wrong tool and Midjourney / Flux win easily. Vector output on dense, multi-element illustrations sometimes ships with messy paths that need manual cleanup in Illustrator. Style training is not zero-effort: bad reference sets produce inconsistent brand matches.

What to pilot. Pick one current design project — say, a 20-icon set or a landing-page illustration system. Build the brand style with 15 references, generate the assets, and measure how many drop straight into Figma vs. how many need cleanup. Above 70% clean-import rate and Recraft replaces a significant chunk of contract illustration spend; below that and you have a useful drafting tool, not a production replacement.', now()),
('Pixelcut (now Pixa)', 'pixelcut', 'Mobile-first AI photo editor for e-commerce sellers — background removal, product mockups, and batch enhancement.', 'Pixelcut rebranded to Pixa in 2024 — the pixelcut.ai domain now 301-redirects to pixa.com, and all features, accounts, and subscriptions carried over to the new name. The product itself is unchanged: a mobile-first AI photo editor purpose-built for e-commerce sellers, marketplace listers (eBay, Etsy, Amazon, Depop), and small-business owners who need fast, professional-looking product imagery without learning Photoshop.

The core toolset is built for one workflow: shoot a product on your phone, remove the background in one tap, drop it into a generated studio scene or a flat color, batch-process the next twenty items in your inventory, and export at marketplace-ready resolutions. Pixa adds AI scene generation (place a sneaker on a beach), shadow synthesis, retouching, magic eraser, photo upscaling, and template-based mockups (T-shirts, mugs, bottles).

Distribution is dominated by the iOS and Android apps, both highly rated and frequently featured by Apple. A web version exists for desktop workflows. The pricing is consumer-grade — a few dollars per month — making it accessible for solo sellers and side-hustle merchants who would never commission product photography.', 'https://www.pixa.com', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["Limited daily edits","Watermark on some exports","Basic background removal"]},{"plan":"Pro","price":"$11.99/mo","features":["Unlimited edits","No watermark","All AI scenes","Batch processing","HD exports"]},{"plan":"Pro Annual","price":"$71.99/yr","features":["All Pro features","50% discount vs monthly"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', false, '{"mobile","web"}', '{"One-tap background removal","AI-generated product scenes and backgrounds","Batch processing for inventory","Magic eraser for unwanted objects","Shadow and reflection synthesis","Photo upscaling and enhancement","Marketplace-ready export presets (eBay, Etsy, Amazon, Shopify)","Mockup templates (apparel, drinkware, packaging)","Mobile-first iOS and Android apps","Web editor for desktop workflows"}', '{"Shopify (via export)","Etsy (via export)","Amazon Seller Central (via export)","eBay (via export)","Instagram (via export)"}', true, '{"E-commerce sellers shooting products on phones","Etsy / eBay / Depop merchants needing fast listing photos","Small businesses without budget for a product photographer","Side-hustle resellers processing daily inventory"}', '{"Professional product photographers (workflow is too consumer)","Brand teams needing pixel-perfect retouch (Photoshop wins)","Users on desktop-only workflows (mobile-first design shows)"}', 'The most polished mobile-first AI photo editor for e-commerce sellers in 2026. Cheap, fast, and the batch workflow saves real hours per week.', '{"https://help.pixa.com/"}', 'Recently rebranded from Pixelcut to Pixa (mid-2024) — older tutorials, App Store reviews, and search results still reference the old name; pixelcut.ai redirects to pixa.com. AI scene generation occasionally produces unrealistic shadows and lighting that don''t match the product. Background removal struggles with hair, fur, and translucent objects (glassware, jewellery wire). Mobile-first means the desktop web editor has fewer features than the apps.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Remove backgrounds and add a clean white scene for 50 Etsy listings in one batch.","Generate lifestyle product shots (a candle on a marble countertop) without a real photo shoot.","Process daily reseller inventory on the phone between sourcing trips.","Create on-brand T-shirt mockups for a Shopify store launch."}', 'Sweet spot: a solo or small-team e-commerce seller who is shooting their own products on a phone and wants the listing photos to look like they came from a studio. Pixa''s batch workflow on mobile is genuinely the fastest way to process a backlog of inventory — paste in twenty raw shots, get twenty marketplace-ready exports in five minutes.

Failure modes. The rebrand transition (Pixelcut → Pixa) means searching for tutorials and reviews requires checking both names — community content under the old brand will keep popping up for at least another year. AI scene generation is good 80% of the time, but the misses are obvious — wrong shadow direction, lighting that doesn''t match the product. For categories with translucent or fine-detail items (jewellery, glassware, textiles), background removal needs manual cleanup. Professional product photographers will not be replaced.

What to pilot. Process 25 real listings from your current inventory in one batch. Compare time, output quality, and conversion-rate proxy (which photos look most professional) against your current workflow. If Pixa cuts your listing-photo time by 50%+ and the photos pass your "would I trust this seller?" sniff test, the $12/mo tier is one of the highest-ROI tools a small seller can buy.', now()),
('Remini', 'remini', 'Mobile AI photo enhancer that restores old photos and generates AI portraits — Bending Spoons subsidiary at ~100M MAU.', 'Remini is a mobile AI photo-enhancement app operated by AI Creativity S.r.l., a subsidiary of Bending Spoons (the Italian app conglomerate that also owns Evernote, WeTransfer, Splice, and Meetup). It crossed roughly 100 million monthly active users in 2024, making it one of the most-used AI consumer apps globally — particularly in Asia, Latin America, and emerging markets.

The core product is photo enhancement: feed it a blurry, low-resolution, or damaged photo and it returns a sharp, restored version with believable facial detail. The 2023–2024 viral moment came from its AI portrait generator, which let users upload selfies and produce stylised LinkedIn-style or studio-style headshots — a feature that drove top-of-charts App Store rankings in dozens of countries.

Beyond portraits, Remini handles old photo restoration (scratches, faded color, missing detail), video enhancement, AI baby generation (predicting how a couple''s child might look), and an expanding set of generative photo features. The product is consumer mobile / web only — no API, no enterprise tier, no developer integration.', 'https://remini.ai', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["Limited daily enhancements","Watermark","Standard quality"]},{"plan":"Pro Weekly","price":"~$9.99/wk","features":["Unlimited enhancements","HD output","No watermark","All AI generators"]},{"plan":"Pro Monthly","price":"~$19.99/mo","features":["All Pro features","Cancel anytime"]},{"plan":"Pro Annual","price":"~$79.99/yr","features":["Best value","All Pro features"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', false, '{"mobile","web"}', '{"AI photo enhancement and upscaling","Old photo restoration (scratches, fading, damage)","AI portrait generator (LinkedIn / studio styles)","AI baby generator","Video enhancement","Face restoration on group shots","Color restoration on black-and-white photos","Mobile-first iOS and Android apps","Web version for desktop"}', '{"Camera Roll (iOS)","Google Photos (Android)","Social media share targets"}', true, '{"Consumers restoring old family photos","Users wanting AI portrait headshots for social or LinkedIn","Casual users enhancing low-quality phone photos","Couples curious about the AI baby feature"}', '{"Developers (no API)","Enterprise / commercial production work","Users needing pixel-faithful restoration (AI invents detail)","Western users on tight budgets (weekly pricing is aggressive)"}', 'The dominant consumer AI photo enhancer globally — ~100M MAU. Best for personal photo restoration and viral generators, not professional work.', '{}', 'Pricing model leans heavily on weekly subscriptions ($9.99/week is common entry) which can surprise users who don''t convert to annual — total annual cost via weekly is ~5x the annual plan. AI face restoration sometimes "smooths" features in ways that change identity, especially on older or lower-resolution sources. No API or developer access — consumer mobile only. As a Bending Spoons app, expect aggressive marketing prompts inside the free tier.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Restore a damaged family photo from the 1970s for a printed gift.","Generate professional-looking LinkedIn headshots from selfies in an afternoon.","Sharpen blurry phone photos of kids or pets to print quality.","Try the AI baby generator with a partner as a one-off novelty."}', 'Sweet spot: a consumer with a specific personal photo job — restoring an old family snapshot, getting decent headshots without paying a photographer, sharpening a meaningful but blurry memory. Remini''s consumer scale (~100M MAU) means the underlying models have been heavily tuned on real-world photo failures, and for the median consumer photo-restore task it produces results that feel magical.

Failure modes. The pricing strategy is the single biggest user complaint — weekly subscriptions are the default entry point and the math punishes users who don''t actively switch to annual. Face restoration on heavily damaged sources will sometimes produce a sharp, beautiful face that is not actually the person in the original photo — which matters for archival or sentimental use. No API means it is unusable in any commercial workflow. As part of Bending Spoons, expect frequent upsell prompts.

What to pilot. Use the free tier on three real photos from your camera roll — one old, one blurry, one for AI portraits. If two of three results clear your bar, switch directly to the annual plan (skip weekly) and use it as a once-a-month tool for personal photo work. If you find yourself wanting it more than monthly, you''re probably not the target user — a desktop tool like Topaz will give you more control.', now()),
('Submagic', 'submagic', 'Auto-caption and edit short-form video for TikTok, Reels, and YouTube Shorts — built for creators.', 'Submagic is a web-based video editor purpose-built for short-form vertical video — TikTok, Instagram Reels, YouTube Shorts. Upload raw footage and Submagic auto-transcribes the audio, generates animated word-by-word captions in popular creator styles (MrBeast, Iman Gadzhi, Alex Hormozi presets, etc), adds B-roll suggestions, sound effects, and zooms to match the talking pace.

The product''s reason for existing is workflow speed. A creator who manually captions a 60-second talking-head clip in CapCut is looking at 20–40 minutes of work; Submagic compresses that to 2–3 minutes of upload and review. For creators publishing daily across multiple short-form platforms, that is the difference between sustainable cadence and burnout.

Beyond captions, the platform adds AI-driven cuts (silence removal, ums and uhs), template-based intros and outros, multi-language captioning (50+ languages), and a growing library of creator-tested styles. It''s built specifically for one persona — short-form creators and the agencies serving them — and its strongest growth channel is its affiliate program, which has turned creator tutorials into a major acquisition engine.', 'https://www.submagic.co', 'paid', '[{"plan":"Starter","price":"$13/mo","features":["10 videos/mo","Up to 5 min per video","Standard styles","HD export"]},{"plan":"Pro","price":"$29/mo","features":["30 videos/mo","Up to 15 min","All styles","B-roll AI"]},{"plan":"Scale","price":"$59/mo","features":["100 videos/mo","Up to 60 min","Priority processing","Team features"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', false, '{"web"}', '{"Auto-captions in 50+ languages","Word-by-word animated captions in creator styles","AI B-roll suggestions and stock library","AI sound effects and music","Auto-zoom on speaker for talking-head pacing","Silence and filler-word removal","Template intros and outros","Multi-format export (9:16, 1:1, 16:9)","Browser-based — no install","Strong creator affiliate program"}', '{"TikTok (via export)","Instagram Reels (via export)","YouTube Shorts (via export)","CapCut (via export)","Final Cut Pro (via export)"}', true, '{"Short-form creators publishing daily on TikTok / Reels / Shorts","Agencies repurposing long-form podcasts into clips","Course creators adding captions to lessons","Solopreneurs scaling personal brand video"}', '{"Long-form YouTube editing (specialised tools win)","Cinematic editing (DaVinci / Premiere)","Free users (no free tier of substance)","Teams needing collaboration features at scale (Pro is single-user-ish)"}', 'The fastest way to caption and polish short-form vertical video in 2026. Caption styles are the killer feature — they look like the creators you actually watch.', '{"https://www.submagic.co/tutorials"}', 'No free tier of practical use — you commit at $13/mo minimum to evaluate properly. Auto-transcription accuracy drops on heavy accents, fast speech, and noisy audio — review before publishing. AI B-roll suggestions are hit-or-miss on niche topics. As a browser-based tool, large uploads on slow connections are painful. Strong creator affiliate program means tutorial reviews online are often financially motivated — discount accordingly when researching.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Caption a daily 60-second TikTok in under 5 minutes instead of 30.","Repurpose a 60-minute podcast into 8 short clips with captions and B-roll for Instagram Reels.","Add multi-language captions to a course-promo video for international launch.","Build a daily short-form publishing cadence as a solo creator without burning out on editing."}', 'Sweet spot: a short-form creator or small agency publishing 3+ vertical videos per week who currently spends an hour per video on captions and pacing in CapCut. Submagic compresses that to 5–10 minutes per video, which over a month is 10–20 hours of recovered time. The MrBeast / Hormozi-style caption presets feel immediately familiar to viewers who consume that content.

Failure modes. Auto-transcription is excellent on clean studio audio and mediocre on real-world recordings — accents, background noise, and overlapping speech all degrade accuracy. The tool is designed for talking-head content; cinematic, music-led, or no-speech videos get little benefit. The pricing requires real volume to justify — at the Starter tier you''re paying $1.30 per video, which only pencils out if your time is worth more than that. Affiliate-driven tutorials oversell — actual workflow gains are real but smaller than influencer demos suggest.

What to pilot. Process 10 real videos from your last week of content. Time the manual workflow you would have done vs. Submagic. If the time saved exceeds the subscription cost at your hourly rate within one month, commit to annual. If not — your content style probably doesn''t fit the talking-head pattern Submagic optimises for, and CapCut + manual captions remains the right tool.', now()),
('Klap', 'klap', 'AI tool that turns long YouTube videos into ready-to-post vertical shorts.', 'Klap is a web app that ingests a long-form YouTube, Vimeo, or uploaded video and produces a batch of short-form, vertical clips ready for TikTok, Instagram Reels, and YouTube Shorts. It picks moments using a virality-scoring model trained on engagement signals, auto-reframes the speaker into 9:16 with face tracking, burns in animated captions, and lets you edit any clip in a built-in timeline before exporting.

The pitch is speed: a 60-minute podcast episode becomes 10 captioned, reframed clips in roughly the time it takes to make a coffee. For creators and marketing teams running a "long video first, then atomise into shorts" content strategy, Klap collapses what was a multi-hour editor task into something a non-editor can do.

Klap sits in a crowded space alongside Opus Clip, Vizard, Submagic, and 2short.ai. Its differentiation is workflow polish — the editor is genuinely usable, AI dubbing across 29 languages is included on Pro, and the highlight-detection has been steadily improving since its 2023 launch. Pricing is per-minute-of-source-video, which matters once you scale beyond a handful of clips a month.', 'https://klap.app', 'paid', '[{"plan":"Starter","price":"$23/mo","features":["10 videos/mo","Up to 45 min each","100 clips/mo","HD download"]},{"plan":"Pro","price":"$63/mo","features":["30 videos/mo","Up to 2 hr each","300 clips/mo","4K download","AI Dubbing in 29 languages"]},{"plan":"Pro+","price":"$151/mo","features":["100 videos/mo","Up to 3 hr each","1000 clips/mo","4K download","AI Dubbing"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', false, '{"web"}', '{"AI highlight detection on long videos","Auto vertical reframing with face tracking","Animated burned-in captions","Built-in clip editor and timeline","AI dubbing across 29 languages (Pro)","4K export (Pro and above)","Direct YouTube and Vimeo URL ingestion","B-roll and emoji suggestions","Bulk batch processing","Brand kit and font customisation"}', '{"YouTube","Vimeo","TikTok","Instagram Reels","YouTube Shorts"}', true, '{"Podcasters atomising long episodes into shorts","Solo creators repurposing webinars and livestreams","Marketing teams running short-form video at scale","Coaches and educators turning talks into clip libraries"}', '{"Editors who need frame-accurate manual control over every cut","Teams producing original short-form (not repurposing) — write in a vertical-first tool","Long-form documentary work"}', 'The fastest long-to-short pipeline in 2026 if your content already exists as 30+ minute videos. Klap handles the boring 80% so you can spend time on titles and thumbnails.', '{}', 'Highlight selection still misses subtle moments — expect to discard 2–3 of every 10 auto-picked clips. Caption accuracy on technical jargon and accented English is good but not perfect; budget time to scan and fix. AI dubbing is convincing on simple speech but loses energy and timing on emphatic delivery. Pricing is per-source-minute, so a 3-hour weekly podcast eats the Starter quota fast.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Turn a weekly 60-minute podcast episode into 10 captioned vertical clips for TikTok and Reels.","Repurpose conference talks and webinars into a YouTube Shorts library.","Translate a long English video into Spanish or Hindi shorts using AI dubbing.","Bulk-process a backlog of long-form interviews into a content calendar."}', 'Sweet spot: a creator or small marketing team that already publishes long-form video and wants the short-form distribution channel without hiring an editor. Klap''s value is the time arbitrage — minutes of effort instead of hours per episode.

Failure modes. Highlight detection is a probability game, not a craft tool — if your content is dense, nuanced, or relies on visual reveals, the auto-picker will miss the best moments and you''ll find yourself fighting it. Pricing scales with source-video minutes, so high-volume podcasters can outgrow the plans quickly; do the math on your weekly source minutes before subscribing.

What to pilot. Run one full episode through Klap end-to-end. Count how many auto-picked clips you''d actually publish without re-editing. If 5 of 10 clear your bar, the time savings justify the subscription; below 3 of 10 and you''ll spend as much time fixing clips as you would editing manually — pick a tool with stronger manual control instead.', now()),
('Avoma', 'avoma', 'All-in-one AI meeting assistant with conversation intelligence and revenue analytics for sales teams.', 'Avoma is an AI meeting platform aimed primarily at revenue teams. It records and transcribes Zoom, Google Meet, and Microsoft Teams calls in 40+ languages, auto-generates structured notes with smart chapters, drafts follow-up emails, and writes the meeting summary back into your CRM. The basic AI Meeting Assistant tier handles the note-taking and summary work that tools like Otter, Fireflies, and Fathom also target.

Where Avoma differentiates is the conversation- and revenue-intelligence layers that sit on top. The Conversation Intelligence add-on adds AI call scoring, talk-pattern analysis, custom topic tracking, and real-time answer assistance during live calls. The Revenue Intelligence module adds deal- and churn-risk alerts, methodology-based scoring (MEDDIC, BANT, SPICED), pipeline reviews, and forecasting — features that overlap heavily with Gong and Chorus at materially lower price points.

Avoma also includes a scheduler and lead router, which means a small sales team can replace Calendly + Otter + Gong with a single contract. That bundling is the core pitch — fewer point tools, one AI layer over the entire meeting lifecycle from booking to deal closure.', 'https://www.avoma.com', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["Limited recordings","Basic AI notes","Personal use"]},{"plan":"AI Meeting Assistant","price":"$19/user/mo (annual)","features":["Recording + transcription","AI notes and summaries","CRM sync","Scheduler"]},{"plan":"Conversation Intelligence","price":"+$29/user/mo (annual)","features":["AI call scoring","Topic tracking","Talk-pattern analysis","Real-time assistance"]},{"plan":"Revenue Intelligence","price":"Custom","features":["Deal and churn risk","Forecasting","Pipeline reviews","Methodology scoring"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","mobile","api"}', '{"Recording and transcription across Zoom / Meet / Teams","AI notes with smart chapters and action items","Follow-up email drafting","CRM auto-sync (Salesforce, HubSpot, Pipedrive)","AI call scoring and methodology tracking","Talk-pattern and topic analytics","Deal- and churn-risk alerts","Forecasting and pipeline reviews","Built-in scheduler and lead router","Real-time answer assistance on live calls"}', '{"Zoom","Google Meet","Microsoft Teams","Salesforce","HubSpot","Pipedrive","Slack","Outreach","Salesloft","Zapier"}', true, '{"SMB and mid-market sales teams replacing Gong / Calendly / Otter","Customer success teams tracking renewal and churn signals","Sales managers running call coaching at scale","Founders running their own pipeline who want forecasting without hiring a RevOps lead"}', '{"Solo users who only need note-taking (cheaper / simpler tools win)","Engineering or design meetings (sales-flavoured features add noise)","Enterprises requiring strict on-prem deployment"}', 'A serious Gong alternative for sales teams under 200 reps — same conversation- and revenue-intelligence shape, materially cheaper, with scheduling bundled in.', '{"https://help.avoma.com/"}', 'AI scoring and forecasting accuracy depends heavily on clean CRM data — garbage in, confidently-wrong predictions out. The Conversation Intelligence add-on roughly doubles per-seat cost; do the math on which seats actually need it. Mobile experience trails the desktop product. Some advanced Gong features (call-library curation, peer benchmarking) are thinner here.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Replace Calendly + Otter + a basic CI tool with one platform for a 20-person sales team.","Auto-score sales calls against MEDDIC and surface coaching moments for managers.","Surface deal- and churn-risk signals without buying Gong.","Run weekly pipeline reviews backed by AI-generated deal summaries."}', 'Sweet spot: a 10–150 rep sales org that has outgrown free Otter / Fireflies and is staring at a Gong contract they can''t justify. Avoma covers most of the same ground at a fraction of the price, and the integrated scheduler removes a separate Calendly bill. For revenue teams in this band, the consolidation case is genuinely strong.

Failure modes. The all-in-one pitch hides per-feature trade-offs — call scoring is solid but not Gong-grade, scheduling is functional but not Chili Piper-grade, forecasting works but won''t replace a dedicated RevOps platform at the upper enterprise end. Privacy: bots join meetings to record, which some prospects flag — have a documented disclosure flow ready.

What to pilot. Roll Avoma out to 5 reps for one full sales cycle. Track three metrics: percentage of calls automatically logged to CRM, time saved on follow-up emails, and rep satisfaction with AI-generated notes. If all three move materially, scale to the team. If notes need heavy editing or CRM sync misfires, the consolidation savings won''t cover the friction.', now()),
('Circleback', 'circleback', 'Y Combinator-backed AI meeting notes app with high-accuracy transcription and workflow automations.', 'Circleback is an AI meeting-notes product from a Y Combinator team focused narrowly on the note-taking and follow-up problem rather than the full sales-intelligence stack. It joins Zoom, Google Meet, Microsoft Teams, and Slack huddle calls (and supports in-person recording on mobile), produces a structured summary with action items automatically assigned to attendees, and powers an AI search across your entire meeting history.

Where it differentiates from Otter, Fireflies, and Fathom is two things: transcription quality on technical vocabulary and accented speakers (consistently rated higher in independent reviews and TIME''s 2024 round-up), and its workflow-automation layer. You can route action items into Linear, Notion, HubSpot, Salesforce, or Slack with rules — "for any sales call, create a HubSpot note and post the action items to #sales-handoff" — without writing Zapier glue.

The product has a free tier ("Try it free. Subscribe if you love it") and a paid tier for unlimited usage and team features. It is single-purpose by design — note-taking done well, not a Gong-style revenue-intelligence platform — which is exactly the appeal for teams that don''t need the full sales suite.', 'https://circleback.ai', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["Limited monthly recordings","Basic AI notes","Personal use"]},{"plan":"Pro","price":"Subscription","features":["Unlimited meetings","Workflow automations","All integrations","AI search across history"]},{"plan":"Team","price":"Per-seat","features":["Shared workspace","Admin controls","Priority support"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","mobile","api"}', '{"Transcription in 100+ languages","Speaker identification","High-accuracy technical-term capture","Auto-assigned action items per attendee","AI search across all past meetings","Workflow automations to 15+ apps","Native Zoom / Meet / Teams / Slack huddle support","In-person recording on mobile","CRM auto-sync (HubSpot, Salesforce)","Custom note templates"}', '{"Zoom","Google Meet","Microsoft Teams","Slack","HubSpot","Salesforce","Linear","Notion","Asana","Google Calendar","Slack","Zapier"}', true, '{"Founders and small teams who want excellent notes without sales-intelligence overhead","Consultants tracking action items across many client calls","Engineering and product teams capturing technical decisions","PMs running cross-functional discovery"}', '{"Sales orgs needing call scoring / deal intelligence (use Gong / Avoma)","Highly regulated environments needing strict on-prem deployment","Teams already happy with the Otter / Fireflies free tiers"}', 'The note-taking-first AI meeting tool to pick if you want one job done very well rather than a full sales-intelligence platform.', '{}', 'Free tier limits monthly recording minutes — heavy users hit the paid wall fast. Workflow automations are powerful but require initial rule-setup time. As a smaller startup vs. Gong / Avoma, the integration roadmap is narrower; check that your CRM and PM tool are first-class. Bot-joining-meetings dynamic still applies — disclose to attendees.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Capture action items from a discovery call and auto-create Linear tickets assigned to each attendee.","Search ''what did we decide about pricing in Q1?'' across 200 past meetings and get a cited answer.","Run a consultancy where every client call routes notes into the right Notion workspace automatically.","Replace Otter for a small team that wants better technical-term accuracy."}', 'Sweet spot: a founder, consultant, or 5–30 person team that has tried Otter or Fireflies and wishes the notes were sharper and the post-meeting workflow automatic. Circleback nails the small set of things it sets out to do, and the automation layer is the under-rated part — it removes the "now go file the action items" tax that kills most note-tools'' value.

Failure modes. As a YC-stage company, the integration list is shorter than incumbents and the roadmap can shift. Don''t buy expecting Gong-style call coaching or deal-risk analytics — that''s not the product. Heavy meeting load (15+ calls a week per person) on the free tier won''t work; budget for paid from day one if you''re a real user.

What to pilot. Run Circleback alongside your current notes tool for two weeks. At the end, compare the action-item lists and CRM-sync correctness side by side. If Circleback wins on accuracy and saves you a measurable chunk of post-meeting filing time, switch; if the gap is small, the cost of changing tools probably isn''t worth it.', now()),
('Cartesia', 'cartesia', 'Real-time, ultra-low-latency text-to-speech API powered by the Sonic state-space voice model.', 'Cartesia is a voice-AI company building Sonic, a state-space-model-based text-to-speech engine optimised for real-time, sub-100ms latency streaming. The pitch to developers is simple: if you are building a voice agent, IVR replacement, or any product where the user is talking to an AI in real time, traditional TTS (ElevenLabs, Google, Azure) introduces latency that breaks conversational feel. Sonic is architected from the ground up for streaming.

The product surface is a clean REST + WebSocket API with SDKs in Python, TypeScript, Go, and Rust, plus a browser playground. It supports 40+ languages, instant 10-second voice cloning, professional voice cloning for commercial use, a curated library of pre-built voices, and inline emotion / laughter expression tags. SOC 2 Type II, HIPAA, and PCI Level 1 compliance are in place — uncommon for the open-research-flavoured TTS space.

Cartesia has become the default voice layer for several real-time AI agent platforms (LiveKit, Pipecat, Retell, Vapi) and is available natively on Together AI''s GPU clusters. For developer teams shipping voice agents in production, it is currently the strongest combination of latency, quality, and reliability.', 'https://cartesia.ai', 'paid', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["Limited monthly characters","Playground access","Standard voices"]},{"plan":"Pro","price":"Subscription","features":["Higher character allowance","Voice cloning","Commercial use","Email support"]},{"plan":"Scale","price":"Usage-based","features":["High-volume API","Professional voice cloning","Priority latency"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"Custom","features":["SLA","HIPAA / PCI","Dedicated capacity","On-prem option"]}]'::jsonb, 'advanced', true, '{"api"}', '{"Sub-100ms model latency for real-time streaming","Sonic state-space voice model","40+ language support","Instant 10-second voice cloning","Professional voice cloning for commercial use","Inline emotion and laughter expression tags","REST + WebSocket APIs","SDKs in Python, TypeScript, Go, Rust","SOC 2 Type II, HIPAA, PCI Level 1 compliance","Browser playground for testing"}', '{"LiveKit","Pipecat","Retell","Vapi","Together AI","Twilio","Deepgram","OpenAI","Anthropic"}', true, '{"Developers building real-time voice agents","Telephony / IVR replacement projects","Game studios needing dynamic NPC dialogue","Accessibility tools needing low-latency narration"}', '{"Non-developers (no GUI product)","One-off audiobook or podcast narration (ElevenLabs is more polished here)","Free / hobby projects (Sonic is paid past a small free tier)"}', 'The default real-time TTS choice in 2026 if you are shipping a voice agent and latency matters more than studio polish. Sonic is state-of-the-art for streaming.', '{"https://docs.cartesia.ai/"}', 'Voice quality on long, narrative reads is excellent but ElevenLabs still edges it on sheer expressive nuance for non-real-time use cases. Pricing scales with characters generated — high-volume voice agents need the Scale tier and careful caching of repeated phrases. Voice cloning ethics and consent are entirely on you; Cartesia provides the tech, not the policy.', '{"sonic","sonic-3"}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Build a real-time voice agent for a telephony product (IVR, sales-dialler, support).","Replace a robotic IVR system with a sub-100ms conversational voice.","Generate dynamic NPC dialogue in a game with emotional expression.","Ship a multilingual accessibility narrator that reacts in real time."}', 'Sweet spot: a developer team building an actual real-time voice agent — phone, app, kiosk — where the user is in a back-and-forth conversation with an AI. Latency is a perceptual cliff in voice UX, and Sonic is one of the few TTS models genuinely engineered for the streaming case rather than batch generation.

Failure modes. If you are generating audio offline (audiobooks, video narration, podcast intros), Sonic''s streaming-first architecture is wasted optimisation; ElevenLabs or Play.ht give more expressive options for that workload at similar cost. Voice cloning legal exposure is non-trivial — if you clone a real person without ironclad consent, the company you''re building is what gets sued, not Cartesia.

What to pilot. Wire Sonic into your real prototype with a real STT (Deepgram, AssemblyAI) and a real LLM, and measure end-to-end perceived latency from user-finishes-speaking to AI-starts-speaking. Below 800ms feels conversational; above 1.5s feels broken. If Sonic gets you under 800ms in your stack, commit; if not, the bottleneck is somewhere else (network, LLM TTFT) and changing TTS won''t fix it.', now()),
('LobeHub', 'lobehub', 'Open-source multi-LLM chat client (LobeChat) plus hosted cloud with agents, plugins, and a skills marketplace.', 'LobeHub (formerly LobeChat) is an open-source AI productivity platform built around a polished multi-model chat UI. The self-hosted edition supports OpenAI, Anthropic, Gemini, DeepSeek, Qwen, Moonshot, Zhipu, Ollama, OpenRouter, and 30+ other providers — drop in your API keys and chat with any of them from the same interface. It runs as a Next.js app you deploy to Vercel, Docker, or your own infra in minutes.

Beyond chat, LobeHub adds a plugin / function-calling system, a vision-and-voice-capable model interface, image generation via DALL-E and SD, custom agents with system prompts and knowledge bases, and a community marketplace of pre-built agent personas and "skills." A growing catalogue of agent skills lets users install task-specific assistants (coding reviewer, translation specialist, copywriter) without building them from scratch.

The hosted LobeHub Cloud tier is currently invite-only with a credit-based pricing model — referrals award additional credits — and bundles all providers behind a single managed bill. For users tired of running their own Vercel deploy, the cloud is the easy button; for developers and privacy-focused users, the open-source self-host is the same product without the managed layer.', 'https://lobehub.com', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Open Source","price":"Free","features":["Self-host on Vercel / Docker","All provider integrations","Plugins and agents","Bring your own API keys"]},{"plan":"Cloud (invite-only)","price":"Credit-based","features":["Managed hosting","All providers behind one bill","Skills marketplace","Referral credits"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', false, '{"web","desktop"}', '{"Multi-model chat UI (OpenAI, Anthropic, Gemini, DeepSeek, Qwen, Ollama, 30+)","Plugin and function-calling system","Image generation (DALL-E, Stable Diffusion)","Vision and voice input / output","Custom agents with system prompts","Skills marketplace with community-built personas","Knowledge-base attachment per agent","One-click deploy to Vercel","Docker self-host option","Cloud-managed tier with credit-based billing"}', '{"OpenAI","Anthropic","Gemini","DeepSeek","Qwen","Moonshot","Zhipu","Ollama","OpenRouter","Azure OpenAI","Vercel","Docker"}', true, '{"Power users juggling multiple LLM providers","Self-hosters who want a polished open-source ChatGPT alternative","Teams running local models via Ollama who need a real UI","Developers exploring agent / skill marketplaces"}', '{"Enterprises needing audited multi-tenant governance","Users who only use one provider (native apps are simpler)","Workflows needing deep on-prem RAG (use AnythingLLM or Dify)"}', 'One of the most polished open-source multi-LLM chat clients in 2026. Self-host edition is the right pick if you already pay per token and want an upgrade over provider-native UIs.', '{"https://lobehub.com/docs/usage/start"}', 'Self-host requires a working Vercel or Docker setup — not zero-effort for non-developers. The cloud tier is invite-only with a credit-based model that can be confusing to budget against. Skills marketplace quality is uneven (community-published, not curated). Multi-user / team governance is lighter than enterprise platforms.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Self-host a polished ChatGPT-style UI on Vercel and bring your own API keys.","Compare GPT-4o, Claude, and Gemini side by side from one interface.","Install community-built agent skills (translator, code reviewer) instead of writing system prompts.","Run Ollama locally and attach LobeHub as the front-end for a fully-private setup."}', 'Sweet spot: a developer or technical power user who already pays per token across 2+ providers and wants a single, attractive UI they control. The one-click Vercel deploy is genuinely fast, and the skills marketplace gives you a low-effort way to try agent patterns without writing prompts from scratch.

Failure modes. The cloud tier''s credit model and invite-only access make it hard to recommend as a turnkey product right now — referral credits are nice in theory but messy in practice for budgeting. Self-hosting means you own the operational work: model-key rotation, vector DB if you enable RAG, deploy maintenance. If you''re not comfortable redeploying when the project ships breaking updates, pick a stable hosted alternative.

What to pilot. Deploy the self-hosted edition on Vercel with your existing OpenAI and Anthropic keys, install 2–3 marketplace skills, and use it as your daily driver for a week. If the UI replaces your habit of jumping between provider apps, the self-host is the right fit; if you find yourself reaching past it for ChatGPT or Claude.ai, you don''t need a unified client and a single subscription is simpler.', now()),
('Tana', 'tana', 'Supertag-based outliner that turns notes into a queryable knowledge graph.', 'Tana is an outliner-first notes app built around a single defining primitive: the supertag. Any node in your outline can be tagged (#meeting, #person, #task, #book), and that tag carries a schema — fields, default views, and behaviors. Tag a node #task and it gets a status field, a due date, and shows up in your tasks view automatically. The result is a knowledge graph that grows out of how you naturally take notes, not a database you have to design upfront.

On top of supertags, Tana layers AI features: chat with your graph, voice-to-note transcription on mobile, AI commands that fill fields or summarise nodes, and a meetings module that captures audio, transcribes, and pulls action items into structured supertags. The product has been steadily shifting toward an AI-meeting workspace pitch through 2025–2026, but the underlying outliner-plus-supertag model is what long-time users stay for.

Tana runs on Mac, Windows, web, iOS, and Android with a free tier (capped at 20k nodes, two workspaces, 500 AI credits) and paid Plus / Pro tiers at $10 / $18 per month. It sits in the same conceptual neighbourhood as Roam Research and Logseq, but the supertag schema layer makes it feel closer to a hand-coded Notion than to a pure outliner.', 'https://tana.inc', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["Up to 20,000 nodes","2 workspaces","500 AI credits/mo","Core supertags + linking"]},{"plan":"Plus","price":"$10/mo","features":["2,000 AI credits/mo","Workspace sharing","Calendar sync","Mobile + desktop apps"]},{"plan":"Pro","price":"$18/mo","features":["5,000 AI credits/mo","Unlimited workspaces","Model selection","Password-protected publishing"]}]'::jsonb, 'intermediate', false, '{"web","desktop","mobile"}', '{"Outliner-first editor with infinite nesting","Supertags with schemas (fields, views, behaviors)","Live queries over the entire graph","AI chat grounded in your nodes","Voice-to-note transcription (mobile)","AI commands to fill fields and summarise","Meetings capture with transcription and action items","Calendar two-way sync","Workspace sharing and per-node permissions","Mac, Windows, Web, iOS, Android"}', '{"Google Calendar","Outlook Calendar","Slack","Zapier","OpenAI","Anthropic","Gemini"}', true, '{"Knowledge workers who think in outlines","Researchers who want a personal knowledge graph","PMs and founders running structured meetings","Tana power users coming from Roam or Logseq"}', '{"Casual note-takers who just want a fast scratchpad","Teams needing strict per-document ACLs and audit logs","People who hate keyboard-driven UIs"}', 'The most powerful outliner on the market in 2026 if you commit to learning it. The supertag model genuinely is novel, not marketing.', '{"https://tana.inc/resources","https://help.tana.inc/"}', 'Steep learning curve — the supertag mental model takes weeks before it pays off. Performance on very large graphs (100k+ nodes) can lag, particularly on cold starts. Mobile apps are functional but trail desktop on power-user features. AI credits cap can feel tight on Plus if you rely on meeting transcription.', '{"gpt-4o","claude-3.5-sonnet","gemini-1.5-pro"}', '{"reddit_threads":["https://www.reddit.com/r/TanaInc/"]}'::jsonb, '{"Capture every meeting, auto-tag attendees with #person, and surface action items in a unified tasks view.","Build a personal CRM where every note about a contact rolls up into their #person node.","Run weekly reviews by querying all #task nodes due this week across every project.","Maintain a research notebook where #paper nodes carry citation, status, and key-quote fields."}', 'Sweet spot: a long-form thinker who already lives in outliners (Roam, Workflowy, Logseq) and is willing to invest a weekend learning supertags. Once the schema clicks, Tana stops feeling like a notes app and starts feeling like a personal database that you happen to write into.

Failure modes. The learning curve is real and it weeds out a lot of users in the first week — the empty Tana doc is genuinely intimidating compared to Apple Notes. Performance degrades on very large graphs, so heavy users start hitting cold-start and search lag at the 50k+ node range. The product''s recent shift toward an AI-meetings pitch can feel disorienting if you signed up for the outliner.

What to pilot. Pick one workflow you already do badly (weekly reviews, meeting notes, reading notes), recreate it in Tana with three or four supertags, and use it for two full weeks before deciding. If supertags are saving you re-typing the same fields over and over, you have found the win; if you are spending more time configuring tags than capturing notes, the tool is fighting your workflow and a simpler app is the right call.', now()),
('Reflect', 'reflect', 'Fast, encrypted, AI-assisted notes app that mirrors how you actually think.', 'Reflect is a note-taking app built around three opinions: notes should be fast, notes should be private, and notes should connect to each other automatically. The editor is keyboard-driven, supports backlinks and bidirectional links between notes, and pages are plain Markdown under the hood. Sync is end-to-end encrypted by default, which is rare in the AI-notes category — Reflect cannot read your data, and neither can the model providers in the way that matters most.

The AI layer is integrated into the editor rather than bolted on as a chat panel. You can ask Reflect to outline a topic, expand bullet points, transcribe a voice memo (powered by Whisper), generate questions from a meeting, or rewrite passages in a chosen voice. Because notes are linked, Reflect can also pull context from the rest of your graph when answering — it is RAG over your own brain.

Pricing is deliberately simple: $10 per month (annual), 14-day trial, single tier. Apps ship for Mac, iOS, and web; integrations cover Google Calendar, Outlook, Readwise, Kindle, and Zapier. The team is small and indie, updates ship frequently, and the product is one of the better-designed AI-notes options in 2026.', 'https://reflect.app', 'paid', '[{"plan":"Pro","price":"$10/mo (annual)","features":["Unlimited notes","E2E encryption","AI assistant (GPT-4 + Whisper)","All integrations","iOS + Mac apps","14-day free trial"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', false, '{"web","desktop","mobile"}', '{"Backlinks and bidirectional links","End-to-end encrypted sync","AI assistant in the editor (outline, expand, rewrite)","Voice memo transcription via Whisper","Daily notes / journaling format","Web clipper (Chrome, Safari)","Kindle highlights and Readwise sync","Calendar integration for meeting notes","Markdown export","Mac, iOS, web"}', '{"OpenAI","Whisper","Google Calendar","Outlook","Readwise","Kindle","Zapier"}', true, '{"Privacy-conscious knowledge workers","Writers and researchers who want links + AI in one place","People who liked Roam but wanted a polished, indie alternative"}', '{"Teams needing collaborative notes (Reflect is single-user)","Android users (no Android app)","Free-tier seekers (no permanent free plan)"}', 'The best AI notes app in 2026 if you care about encryption and a fast keyboard-driven editor. Single-user only is the main limit.', '{"https://reflect.app/academy"}', 'No Android app — iOS and Mac only on mobile/desktop. No real-time collaboration; this is a single-user product. AI features still call OpenAI under the hood, so the E2E claim covers your stored notes but content sent to the AI provider transits their infrastructure during the call. No free tier beyond the 14-day trial.', '{"gpt-4","whisper"}', '{"reddit_threads":["https://www.reddit.com/r/reflectnotes/"]}'::jsonb, '{"Keep an end-to-end encrypted journal you actually trust to be private.","Capture meeting notes that auto-link to the #person and #project pages they touch.","Transcribe voice memos on a walk and have Reflect outline them by the time you sit down.","Build a personal research wiki linked to your Kindle highlights and web clippings."}', 'Sweet spot: an individual knowledge worker who wants a Roam-style linked-notes experience with a polished UI, real iOS app, and credible privacy story. Reflect is the rare app where the defaults are good enough that you can start using it on day one and only customise later.

Failure modes. Single-user only is a hard wall — if you need shared notebooks with a teammate, Reflect is the wrong product. The lack of an Android app excludes a meaningful chunk of users. Pricing is a flat $10 with no free tier, which makes it harder to commit to as a side experiment compared to free competitors like Logseq.

What to pilot. Take the 14-day trial seriously: import (or rewrite) one existing notebook, set up daily notes for two weeks, and run the AI features on real content rather than test prompts. If the keyboard flow feels faster than your current app and the AI suggestions are usable rather than generic, the $10 will be the cheapest productivity tool in your stack; if not, Obsidian or Logseq will give you 80% of the linking story for free.', now()),
('Heptabase', 'heptabase', 'Visual whiteboard-based notes app for deep research and learning.', 'Heptabase is a notes app built around the whiteboard, not the document. You write atomic note cards, then arrange them spatially on infinite whiteboards, group them visually, and connect them with arrows. The mental model is closer to a researcher''s wall of index cards than to Notion or Evernote — it is designed for the messy middle of thinking, where you have many small ideas and need to see them in relation before they collapse into a final document.

The product layers serious AI features on top: an AI tutor that runs structured Socratic learning sessions over your notes, AI-generated insight cards that surface connections across your graph, PDF chat with citations, and OCR over scanned pages. Cards are first-class — bidirectional links, tags, and a card-level editor with block primitives — and everything works offline-first with end-to-end sync.

Pricing is tiered around AI usage: Pro at ~$8.99/mo (annual) for unlimited notes but limited AI credits, Premium at ~$17.99/mo adding unlimited PDF uploads and full AI access, and Premium+ for power users who burn through AI credits. Apps ship for Mac, Windows, iOS, Android, and web. Funded by Y Combinator, Kleiner Perkins, and others — well-resourced for the indie note-app category.', 'https://heptabase.com', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free Trial","price":"7 days","features":["Full Pro features for evaluation"]},{"plan":"Pro","price":"$8.99/mo (annual)","features":["Unlimited notes + whiteboards","100 AI credits/mo","Real-time collaboration","All apps"]},{"plan":"Premium","price":"$17.99/mo (annual)","features":["1,800 AI credits/mo","Unlimited PDF uploads","OCR","AI tutor"]},{"plan":"Premium+","price":"Higher tier","features":["8,100 AI credits/mo","Power-user AI workflows"]}]'::jsonb, 'intermediate', false, '{"web","desktop","mobile"}', '{"Infinite whiteboards with spatial card arrangement","Atomic note cards with bidirectional links","AI tutor for structured learning sessions","Insight cards that surface graph connections","PDF annotation and chat with citations","OCR for scanned documents","Web clipper","Real-time collaboration","Offline-first sync","Mac, Windows, iOS, Android, web"}', '{"Readwise","Zotero","OpenAI","Anthropic"}', true, '{"Researchers and PhD students managing literature","Writers and creators developing long-form ideas","Visual thinkers who hate document-first apps","Self-directed learners using AI tutoring"}', '{"Quick scratchpad note-takers (overkill)","Teams needing strict per-doc permissions","Users who prefer linear documents to spatial canvases"}', 'The strongest visual-canvas notes app in 2026 for deep research workflows. The whiteboard is not a gimmick — it changes how you think.', '{"https://heptabase.com/learn"}', 'AI credits are tightly metered — heavy users will hit the Pro tier ceiling fast and need to upgrade. Whiteboard-first is a feature for some and a barrier for others; if you mostly write linearly, the spatial UI adds friction. Mobile apps are usable but the whiteboard experience is best on a large screen. Collaboration is real-time but lighter than Notion or Figma on team workflows.', '{"gpt-4o","claude-3.5-sonnet"}', '{"reddit_threads":["https://www.reddit.com/r/heptabase/"]}'::jsonb, '{"Build a literature review by clipping cards from 50 papers and arranging them spatially by argument.","Use the AI tutor to drill yourself on a textbook''s key concepts before an exam.","Develop a long essay by drafting atomic ideas as cards, then connecting them on a whiteboard before writing.","Annotate a stack of PDFs and chat across all of them with citations back to the source page."}', 'Sweet spot: a researcher, grad student, or long-form writer who is doing genuine synthesis work — reading many sources, finding connections, and producing something original. Heptabase''s whiteboard is the right surface for that kind of work in a way that document-shaped tools simply are not.

Failure modes. The whiteboard is a commitment: if your work is mostly linear (project management, daily journaling, meeting notes), Heptabase will feel heavy compared to a plain outliner. Pricing tiers around AI credits mean serious users get nudged toward Premium+, which gets expensive. Multi-user collaboration exists but is not the focus — pick Notion or FigJam if team workflows matter more than personal depth.

What to pilot. Use the 7-day trial on a real research project, not a toy notebook. Clip 30 sources, build one whiteboard, and write a 1,000-word output from it. If the spatial arrangement helped you see connections you would have missed in a linear app, Heptabase has earned its place; if you ended up writing the same way you always do, a cheaper outliner will serve you fine.', now()),
('Humata AI', 'humata-ai', 'Chat with PDFs and document sets — citations, OCR, and team-shared knowledge.', 'Humata AI is a document-chat product aimed at researchers, students, and knowledge teams who need to interrogate large PDFs (papers, contracts, manuals, reports) in natural language. Upload a document, ask a question, and Humata returns an answer with inline citations linking back to the exact pages. The UX is closer to a serious research tool than to ChatGPT — the citation panel and source-grounding are first-class, not bolted on.

Beyond single-document chat, Humata supports folders, multi-document queries (ask one question across a whole folder), team workspaces with permissions, OCR for scanned PDFs, and a Chrome extension for in-browser document handling. The Team and Enterprise tiers add SSO, audit logs, department-level permissions, and response personalisation for shared knowledge bases.

Pricing tiers: Free (60 pages, 10 answers — useful only as a sample), Expert at $9.99/mo (500 free pages, then $0.02/page), Team at $49/user/mo (5,000 pages, $0.01/extra), and Enterprise on quote. The page-based pricing is unusual and rewards low-volume use; once you cross thousands of pages a month, the math shifts toward Team or Enterprise.', 'https://humata.ai', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["60 pages","10 answers","Basic features"]},{"plan":"Expert","price":"$9.99/mo","features":["500 pages free, then $0.02/page","3 users","Premium chat support"]},{"plan":"Team","price":"$49/user/mo","features":["5,000 pages free, then $0.01/page","10 users","OCR","Department permissions","Response personalisation"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"Custom","features":["Unlimited team size","SSO","Custom contracts","Dedicated support"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"Chat with single PDFs or full folders","Inline citations linking back to source pages","OCR for scanned documents (Team+)","Multi-document queries across a folder","Team workspaces with permissions","Response personalisation per workspace","Chrome extension for in-browser use","API access (paid tiers)","SSO and audit logs (Enterprise)","Page-based pricing"}', '{"Google Drive","Dropbox","Chrome","OpenAI"}', true, '{"Researchers running literature reviews","Lawyers and analysts working through long contracts and reports","Customer-support teams making product manuals queryable","Students summarising textbooks and study material"}', '{"Heavy daily users on the cheapest plan (page costs add up)","Teams that need fully on-prem document handling","Users who only need single-document chat occasionally (free tier of competitors covers it)"}', 'A solid, citation-first document-chat tool with real team features. Page-based pricing is the catch — model your usage before committing.', '{"https://humata.ai/blog"}', 'Page-based pricing punishes high-volume use unless you upgrade to Team. OCR quality is good but not flawless on degraded scans. Cross-document answer quality drops as the folder size grows past a few hundred PDFs — chunking and retrieval limits show. No on-prem option below Enterprise; data leaves your infrastructure on every query.', '{"gpt-4o"}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Chat with a 200-page contract and pull every clause that mentions liability with page citations.","Run a literature review by uploading 30 papers into a folder and asking comparative questions.","Make a product knowledge base of manuals queryable for customer-support agents.","Summarise a textbook chapter and quiz yourself with citations back to the source pages."}', 'Sweet spot: a researcher, paralegal, analyst, or student who routinely deals with long, dense PDFs and needs citations they can verify. Humata''s citation panel is the right shape for that work — you do not just get an answer, you get the page numbers to confirm it.

Failure modes. The page-based pricing means heavy users on the Expert plan can quietly accumulate per-page charges and end up paying more than a flat-fee competitor. OCR is reliable on clean scans but struggles with low-quality images, which matters for older legal or academic material. Cross-folder retrieval starts to drift as document count grows — for a 1,000-PDF knowledge base you want a purpose-built RAG stack, not a doc-chat product.

What to pilot. Upload a folder of 20 PDFs that represent your actual work, ask 30 real questions, and verify every citation. If accuracy is above 90% and the page math fits your volume, Humata earns the subscription; if citations point to the wrong pages or accuracy degrades on cross-document questions, fall back to a self-hosted RAG using Crawl4AI plus a vector DB.', now()),
('ChatPDF', 'chatpdf', 'Popular consumer-friendly chat-with-PDF app — fast, simple, and free for casual use.', 'ChatPDF is one of the most-used document-chat tools on the web, with a deliberately simple UX: drop a PDF, ask questions, get answers with citations to source pages. No account is required to try it on a couple of documents per day, which is part of why the product spread so quickly — the friction from "I have a PDF" to "I have an answer" is about ten seconds. The free tier is genuinely usable for occasional needs, not a pure tease.

Beyond the basics, ChatPDF supports multiple file formats (PDF, Word, PowerPoint, Markdown, plain text), multi-file conversations within folders, side-by-side document viewing with citations highlighted on the page, summarisation, translation, and an embed widget that lets publishers add a "chat with this document" button to their own sites. The model layer routes between GPT-4o and GPT-4o-mini for cost and quality balance.

Pricing: Free (2 documents per day, basic features), and ChatPDF Plus at around $19.99/mo for unlimited documents, files up to 2,000 pages, 32 MB per file, unlimited questions, and additional features. There is also a team / enterprise option for organisations that need shared workspaces and SSO. Compared to Humata, ChatPDF leans more consumer-friendly; compared to NotebookLM, it leans more transactional.', 'https://chatpdf.com', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["2 documents/day","Basic chat","No account required for trial","Citations"]},{"plan":"Plus","price":"~$19.99/mo","features":["Unlimited documents","Files up to 2,000 pages","32 MB per file","Unlimited questions","Multi-file folders"]},{"plan":"Team / Enterprise","price":"Custom","features":["Shared workspaces","SSO","Priority support","Higher limits"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"Chat with PDFs, Word, PowerPoint, Markdown, text","Side-by-side document viewing with citation highlights","Multi-file folders for cross-document conversations","Document summarisation","Translation","Embed widget for publishers","No-account trial mode","API access for developers","Mobile-friendly web app","GPT-4o + GPT-4o-mini routing"}', '{"OpenAI","Stripe","Embed (publisher widget)"}', true, '{"Students summarising textbooks and lecture PDFs","Casual users with occasional document-chat needs","Publishers adding chat-with-document widgets to articles","Professionals interrogating one-off contracts and reports"}', '{"Teams needing strict data residency or on-prem","Users with very large knowledge bases (purpose-built RAG fits better)","Privacy-sensitive workflows (uploads transit a third-party)"}', 'The most accessible chat-with-PDF tool on the market. The free tier is enough for many users; Plus is a fair upgrade if you cross the daily limit.', '{"https://www.chatpdf.com/blog"}', 'Documents are stored on third-party infrastructure during processing — not appropriate for confidential material without an enterprise agreement. Cross-document quality is fine on a handful of PDFs but degrades on large folders. The embed widget customisation is limited compared to building your own RAG. Free tier is generous but capped at 2 documents per day, which trips power users.', '{"gpt-4o","gpt-4o-mini"}', '{"reddit_threads":["https://www.reddit.com/r/ChatGPT/search/?q=chatpdf"]}'::jsonb, '{"Drop a 100-page research paper and have a working summary plus Q&A in under a minute.","Translate a non-English PDF and chat with the translated content side by side.","Embed a chat-with-this-doc widget on a documentation site so readers can ask questions in-line.","Compare three vendor proposals in one folder and ask the model which terms differ."}', 'Sweet spot: a student, professional, or casual user who has a single PDF they need to understand, fast, with no setup. ChatPDF nails that workflow — drag, drop, ask, done. The free tier is generous enough that many users never need to pay, which is rare in this category.

Failure modes. Confidentiality is the real issue: documents transit a third party, so anything sensitive (legal, medical, regulated) belongs on a self-hosted RAG, not ChatPDF. Cross-document quality plateaus around a few dozen PDFs — beyond that, retrieval drift gets visible. The Plus tier at ~$20 is reasonable, but if you are crossing 2 documents/day regularly you should also evaluate Humata or NotebookLM before committing.

What to pilot. Use the free tier for a week against your real workflow. Track how often you hit the 2-document limit and whether citations point to the right pages. If you upgrade, it should be because the daily limit blocks real work, not because the marketing copy promised more than the free tier already delivers — most casual users genuinely do not need Plus.', now()),
('You.com', 'you-com', 'AI-first search engine and web search API built for LLMs and agents.', 'You.com started as a consumer AI search alternative to Google and has since pivoted hard into the API business. The consumer product (you.com) gives you a chat-style search interface with multi-model access — GPT, Claude, Gemini — sitting on top of a real-time web index. The bigger story today is the API layer: Search API, Contents API, and Research API, which are sold as the web-grounding layer behind other AI products.

Where it differs from a generic Google scrape is the index is purpose-built for LLM consumption. Results come back as clean structured snippets with source URLs, optional full-page content, and a research-grade DeepSearchQA endpoint that handles multi-hop questions instead of single-keyword lookups. The company publishes benchmark numbers on SimpleQA and FRAMES and claims sub-300ms p99 latency on the search endpoint.

Customers cited on the site include OpenAI, Amazon, Alibaba, and DuckDuckGo, which is a meaningful signal that the API is being used as infrastructure rather than as a curiosity. Pricing is tiered with a free trial and usage-based plans above it; enterprise tiers add SOC 2, zero data retention, and DPAs. For builders who need a web-search tool call inside an agent without writing scraping infrastructure, You.com is one of the three or four real options.', 'https://you.com', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free Trial","price":"Free credits","features":["Search API access","Test all endpoints","Limited monthly volume"]},{"plan":"Usage-based","price":"Pay-as-you-go","features":["Search API","Contents API","Research API","Higher rate limits"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"Custom","features":["SOC 2","Zero data retention","DPA","Dedicated support","SLA"]}]'::jsonb, 'intermediate', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"Search API with sub-300ms p99 latency","Contents API for full-page extraction across multiple URLs","Research API (DeepSearchQA) for multi-hop questions","Consumer chat UI with multi-model access (GPT, Claude, Gemini)","Real-time web index purpose-built for LLM consumption","Structured snippet output with source URLs","Zero data retention option","SOC 2 certified","DPA-ready for enterprise"}', '{"OpenAI","Anthropic","Gemini","LangChain","LlamaIndex","Vercel AI SDK"}', true, '{"Developers building agents that need a web-search tool call","AI products that need fresh web grounding for answers","Research workflows requiring multi-hop search","Teams replacing scraped Google SERPs with a stable API"}', '{"Consumer users who already have ChatGPT or Perplexity (overlap)","Workflows that only need a single static-page fetch (cheaper tools exist)"}', 'A serious web-search API option for agent builders. The consumer chat product is fine but the API is the real reason to look here.', '{"https://documentation.you.com/"}', 'The consumer product is overshadowed by Perplexity and ChatGPT search; most of You.com''s momentum is now on the API side. Pricing for high-volume use is in the same band as Exa and Tavily, so cost-shop. Index freshness on long-tail / non-English content lags Google, which can show up on niche queries.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Add a fresh-web tool call to a Claude or GPT agent in production.","Build a research agent that answers multi-hop questions with cited sources.","Extract clean page content for a RAG pipeline without writing your own scraper.","Replace ad-hoc Google scraping in a competitive intelligence workflow with a stable API."}', 'Sweet spot: a developer who needs a web-search endpoint behind an agent and wants a vendor with real enterprise paperwork (SOC 2, ZDR, DPA) instead of a hobby API. The Research API specifically — DeepSearchQA — is the differentiated product; if you only need raw search results, Tavily and Exa are direct competitors and you should price all three.

Failure modes. The consumer product is not the moat — anyone evaluating You.com on its chat UI alone will likely prefer Perplexity. Pricing creep is real once you cross a few hundred thousand calls a month; lock down rate limits before going live. Index quality varies by domain — run your own eval set on the queries your users actually ask before committing.

What to pilot. Take 50 representative queries from your product, run them through You.com Search and Contents APIs, score result relevance against a baseline (Google SERP API or Tavily). If You.com wins on latency and result quality at acceptable cost, it is a defensible pick; otherwise the alternative wins on price-performance.', now()),
('Kagi', 'kagi', 'Paid, ad-free premium search engine with strong privacy posture and built-in AI assistant.', 'Kagi is a subscription search engine that flips the standard model: instead of ads paying for your search results, you do. There is no ad layer, no tracking, no SEO-spam farms in the top results, and Kagi explicitly does not sell or use your queries to train models. The trade-off is a monthly fee (free trial with 100 searches, then paid plans) — but for users who have spent the last decade watching Google SERPs decay, the math works.

Beyond search, Kagi ships a tightly integrated set of tools: Kagi Assistant (chat with Claude, GPT, Gemini, and other models behind one bill), Universal Summarizer (summarise any URL or video), Kagi Translate, Small Web (a curated index of personal blogs and indie sites), and the Orion browser for Mac/iOS. Power-user features include site rankings (boost / block / never-show specific domains), lenses (saved search filters), and !bangs ported from DuckDuckGo.

Kagi is a small, profitable, independent company with a clear ideological stance — humans first, no ads, user-funded — that resonates with a specific segment of users. It is not trying to replace Google for everyone. It is trying to be the best paid search engine for people who care about result quality, privacy, and not being the product.', 'https://kagi.com', 'paid', '[{"plan":"Trial","price":"Free (100 searches)","features":["Full search","Limited usage","No card required"]},{"plan":"Starter","price":"$5/mo","features":["300 searches/mo","Full search features","Lenses","Site rankings"]},{"plan":"Professional","price":"$10/mo","features":["Unlimited searches","Kagi Assistant included","Universal Summarizer","Translate"]},{"plan":"Ultimate","price":"$25/mo","features":["Everything in Pro","All AI models in Assistant (Claude Opus, GPT, Gemini Pro)","Higher rate limits"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","mobile","desktop","api"}', '{"Ad-free premium search results","No tracking, no query selling, no model training on user data","Site rankings (boost, block, lower, pin domains)","Lenses (saved scoped searches)","Kagi Assistant — multi-model chat (Claude, GPT, Gemini, more)","Universal Summarizer for URLs and videos","Kagi Translate","Small Web index (curated personal sites and blogs)","Orion browser (Mac, iOS)","Search API for developers"}', '{"Claude","OpenAI","Gemini","Mistral","DeepSeek","Orion browser"}', true, '{"Privacy-conscious users tired of ad-laden SERPs","Researchers who need clean, un-SEO''d results","Developers wanting a paid search API with strong privacy guarantees","Power users willing to pay for a better default search"}', '{"Users unwilling to pay for search","Heavy local / image / shopping searchers (Google still wins on those verticals)","Teams needing shared workspace billing (single-user accounts)"}', 'The best paid search engine for people who care about result quality and privacy. The Ultimate tier with all-models Assistant is genuinely competitive with ChatGPT Plus.', '{"https://help.kagi.com/kagi/"}', 'Index size and freshness lag Google on long-tail and very recent content; Kagi blends results from multiple providers but is not a full independent crawl. Image, shopping, and maps verticals are weak. Pricing is high enough that casual searchers will not see the ROI — the value compounds for daily heavy users.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Replace Google as your daily search engine without ads or tracking.","Run a research session where SEO spam destroys default Google results.","Use Kagi Assistant as a single bill for Claude, GPT, and Gemini access.","Build a search-grounded app on the Kagi Search API with privacy guarantees."}', 'Sweet spot: someone who searches the web 50+ times a day, has noticed Google''s quality decay over the last few years, and is willing to pay $10–$25/month for a result page they actually trust. The Ultimate tier doubles as a multi-model AI subscription, which makes the price comparison vs. ChatGPT Plus + a search engine surprisingly favourable.

Failure modes. If you mostly search for shopping, local businesses, or images, Kagi is worse than Google by a clear margin and you will resent the bill. The site-rankings and lenses features are powerful but require setup — users who never tune them get a less differentiated experience. The free trial is small (100 searches) and many people burn through it before they have learned the workflow.

What to pilot. Take the 14-day or 100-search trial and force yourself to use Kagi as your default for two weeks. Tune site rankings as you go (block content farms, boost docs sites you trust). At the end, compare your subjective satisfaction with results quality against Google. If Kagi wins on more than half your real searches, the subscription pays for itself in time saved.', now()),
('Exa', 'exa', 'Web search API for AI agents with embedding-based retrieval and structured outputs.', 'Exa is a developer-first web search API designed from the ground up for AI applications. Where Google indexes pages for keyword queries, Exa indexes pages as embeddings and supports neural / semantic search out of the box — you can ask for "startups working on agentic browsers in 2025" and get a ranked list of pages that match the meaning, not just the keywords. It also supports traditional keyword search if you need it.

The product surface is four endpoints: Search (semantic or keyword), Contents (extract clean text, summaries, or highlights from a URL), Answer (a one-shot answer endpoint that does the search-and-synthesise step in one call), and Websets (a structured-data product that turns natural-language queries into curated lists of companies, people, papers, etc, backed by a 70M+ company database). Highlights are a token-efficient feature that returns just the relevant 1–3 sentences from a page, which can cut LLM input cost dramatically on RAG flows.

Customers include Cursor, AWS, Databricks, HubSpot, Groq, and Monday.com — Exa has positioned itself as serious infrastructure, not a hobby project. SOC 2 Type II, SSO, and Zero Data Retention options are available on enterprise tiers. For builders who need a search tool call inside an agent and want neural retrieval as a first-class feature, Exa is one of the strongest picks.', 'https://exa.ai', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["Free monthly credits","All endpoints","Test in dashboard"]},{"plan":"Pay-as-you-go","price":"Per-call pricing","features":["Search","Contents","Answer","Websets"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"Custom","features":["SOC 2 Type II","Zero data retention","SSO","Dedicated support","SLA"]}]'::jsonb, 'intermediate', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"Neural / semantic search via embeddings","Keyword search mode","Contents API with text, summaries, and highlights","Answer API for one-shot grounded answers","Websets — structured natural-language queries against a 70M+ company DB","Highlights feature (token-efficient relevant snippets)","Sub-180ms latency on Exa Instant","Specialised indexes (people, companies, code, financial, news)","SOC 2 Type II","SSO and ZDR for enterprise"}', '{"OpenAI","Anthropic","LangChain","LlamaIndex","Vercel AI SDK","Cursor","Databricks"}', true, '{"Developers building AI agents that need web search","RAG pipelines that benefit from semantic retrieval","Sales / research tools needing structured company data","Teams replacing brittle Google scraping with a stable API"}', '{"Consumer chat use cases (no end-user UI)","Workflows that only need a single static fetch","Teams without engineering capacity to integrate an API"}', 'The strongest neural search API for AI agents in 2026. The Highlights feature is the cost-saving detail most teams underestimate.', '{"https://docs.exa.ai/reference/getting-started"}', 'Pricing is per-call and can stack up on agentic workloads that issue many searches per task — set rate limits and cache aggressively. Neural search quality depends on phrasing; keyword fallback exists for a reason. Index coverage on very fresh news (last few hours) and non-English content is thinner than Google.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Power a Cursor-style coding assistant with semantic search over docs and Stack Overflow.","Build a sales-research tool that turns ''AI startups in healthcare'' into a structured list of companies.","Add neural retrieval to a RAG pipeline so semantic queries beat exact-match keyword search.","Replace LangChain''s default web search tool with Exa for higher-quality grounding."}', 'Sweet spot: a developer building an agent or RAG pipeline who has hit the limits of keyword search and wants semantic retrieval that just works. Exa''s Highlights endpoint is genuinely undervalued — for high-volume RAG it can cut LLM input cost by an order of magnitude versus shipping full pages into context.

Failure modes. Exa is API-only — there is no end-user UI, so this is not the tool to pick if you do not have an engineer to integrate it. Costs can grow non-linearly on multi-hop agent flows; profile your typical task before committing. Websets is powerful but data freshness on the company database varies by sector, so spot-check before relying on it for sales workflows.

What to pilot. Take the queries your product actually issues, run them through Exa Search and Contents (with Highlights enabled), measure relevance against your current solution and total token cost end-to-end. If Exa wins on relevance at lower combined cost, the migration is worth the engineering hours; if it ties on relevance at higher cost, stay where you are.', now()),
('Glasp', 'glasp', 'Social web highlighter with AI summaries — capture, organise, and resurface what you read online.', 'Glasp is a browser extension and web app that lets you highlight passages on any webpage, PDF, or YouTube transcript and saves them to a personal collection that is searchable across everything you have ever marked. Think of it as Kindle highlights for the entire internet, with a social layer on top: you can follow other users, see what they are highlighting, and discover content through their reading trails.

The AI layer added over the last two years is the reason it shows up in tool directories now. Glasp generates AI summaries of YouTube videos (using ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini, or Mistral as the user picks), AI summaries of webpages and PDFs grounded in your highlights, and an "AI clone" feature that builds a personalised assistant trained on your highlights and notes — useful for researchers and writers who want their reading history to be queryable.

It is free for the basic tier (unlimited public highlights, ~100 YouTube summaries/month, basic PDF support), with a Pro tier around $10/mo (annually) that adds private highlights, advanced summary models, larger PDF and audio quotas, and more storage. The product is well-loved by a niche of researchers, students, and content creators — not a mass-market tool, but very sticky for the audience it serves.', 'https://glasp.co', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["Unlimited public highlights","Basic YouTube summaries (~100/mo)","PDF uploads (~5/mo)","Audio transcription (30 min/mo)","Browser extension"]},{"plan":"Pro","price":"$10/mo (annual)","features":["Unlimited private highlights","Advanced YouTube summaries (1000/mo)","PDF uploads (~100/mo)","Audio transcription (300 min/mo)","Priority support"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', false, '{"web","plugin"}', '{"Highlight any webpage, PDF, or YouTube transcript","Searchable cross-source highlight library","AI summaries of YouTube videos (ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini, Mistral)","AI summaries of webpages and PDFs grounded in highlights","AI clone trained on your highlights and notes","Social discovery — follow other users, see their highlights","Public highlight pages for sharing","Notion / Obsidian / Readwise export","Browser extension (Chrome, Edge, Safari, Firefox)"}', '{"Notion","Obsidian","Readwise","ChatGPT","Claude","Gemini","Mistral"}', true, '{"Researchers tracking quotes across many sources","Students building digital notebooks across web and PDF reading","Content creators mining their reading history for ideas","Lifelong learners who want a permanent searchable highlight archive"}', '{"Teams needing shared workspaces (Glasp is single-user-centric)","Users who already live in Readwise (significant overlap)","Privacy-strict users wanting fully local-only storage"}', 'A genuinely lovable highlighter app with a useful AI summary layer on top. The cross-source library — web + PDF + YouTube in one search — is the feature that wins users over.', '{"https://blog.glasp.co/"}', 'The social / discovery layer is thin compared to a true social network — it is more "shared notebooks" than Twitter for readers. AI summary quality depends on the model you pick and the highlights you fed in; bad highlights produce bad summaries. The free tier YouTube summary cap (100/mo) is hit quickly by heavy users, and the Pro tier is required for private highlights, which some new users do not realise upfront.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Highlight ten YouTube videos this week and ask the AI clone what themes recur.","Build a research notebook for a paper across 50 webpages and 20 PDFs.","Capture supporting quotes for a blog post directly from the browser as you read.","Export your year of highlights to Notion as a personal knowledge base."}', 'Sweet spot: an individual researcher, student, writer, or curious heavy reader who wants every highlight from every source in one searchable library and is willing to pay $10/mo for the AI features once they are hooked. Glasp''s biggest virtue is that it is genuinely easy — install the extension, highlight as you read, and the library builds itself.

Failure modes. If you already use Readwise + Reader, Glasp''s feature set is largely overlapping and you should not switch unless the social discovery or YouTube-summary depth specifically pulls you. The "AI clone" is a clever feature but the quality scales with how much you have highlighted — new users get a thin assistant. Privacy-strict users should note that public highlights are the default; you must upgrade to Pro for private mode.

What to pilot. Install the extension, use Glasp as your only highlighter for two weeks across web, PDF, and YouTube. At the end, search your library for a topic you read about and see whether the right highlights surface. If they do, the lock-in starts there; if not, your usage was probably too thin and either Readwise or just bookmarking is fine.', now()),
('Firecrawl', 'firecrawl', 'LLM-friendly web scraper API that turns any site into clean Markdown or structured JSON.', 'Firecrawl is a hosted web-scraping API designed for AI applications. Point it at a URL and you get back clean Markdown, JSON, or screenshots — no Playwright setup, no proxy fiddling, no boilerplate stripping. The product surface is four endpoints: Scrape (single URL to clean output), Crawl (entire site), Map (cheap URL discovery), and Search (search results with full page contents inline). Recently added: Interact, which can click buttons and fill forms before scraping, and Extract, which uses an LLM to turn pages into a JSON schema you define.

The pitch versus rolling your own scraper is straightforward: Firecrawl handles JavaScript-heavy pages, rotates IPs, manages browser pools, retries failures, and outputs LLM-ready Markdown out of the box. P95 latency is ~3.4s across millions of pages and they claim 96% web coverage including JS-heavy sites. There is also an MCP server, so any MCP-compatible AI assistant (Claude Desktop, Cursor, Windsurf) can scrape on demand.

It is open-source at the core (self-host if you want) but most users run on the hosted cloud. Pricing scales by credits — free tier is 500 credits/mo, Hobby is $19/mo for 3,000, Standard $99/mo for 100k, up to Scale at $749/mo for 1M credits. For teams building RAG pipelines, agents, or competitive-intel scrapers, Firecrawl has become one of the default picks alongside Apify and ScrapingBee.', 'https://firecrawl.dev', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["500 credits/mo","All endpoints","Community support"]},{"plan":"Hobby","price":"$19/mo","features":["3000 credits/mo","All endpoints","Email support"]},{"plan":"Standard","price":"$99/mo","features":["100k credits/mo","Higher concurrency","Priority support"]},{"plan":"Growth","price":"$399/mo","features":["500k credits/mo","Higher concurrency","SLA-lite"]},{"plan":"Scale","price":"$749/mo","features":["1M credits/mo","Highest concurrency","Priority support"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"Custom","features":["Custom credits","Dedicated infra","Self-hosted option","SLA"]}]'::jsonb, 'intermediate', true, '{"api","cli"}', '{"Scrape endpoint — URL to clean Markdown / JSON / screenshot","Crawl endpoint — full-site recursive scraping","Map endpoint — fast URL discovery","Search endpoint — SERP results with inline page content","Interact — click buttons and fill forms before scraping","Extract — LLM-driven schema extraction","JS rendering and proxy rotation handled","MCP server for Claude, Cursor, Windsurf","Open-source self-host option","Caching and smart content waiting"}', '{"OpenAI","Anthropic","LangChain","LlamaIndex","Dify","Flowise","Claude Desktop","Cursor","Windsurf"}', true, '{"Developers feeding RAG pipelines from web sources","Agent builders who need a scrape tool call","Sales and competitive-intel teams ingesting external sites","Product teams adding ''import from URL'' features"}', '{"One-off scrapes of a single static page (curl is enough)","Sites with strict ToS forbidding scraping","Workflows already deeply built on Apify or self-hosted Playwright"}', 'The fastest way to go from "list of URLs" to "clean LLM-ready text" without owning a scraping stack. The Extract endpoint is the underrated feature for structured pulls.', '{"https://docs.firecrawl.dev/"}', 'Aggressive anti-bot sites (Cloudflare Turnstile, Datadome, PerimeterX) still block Firecrawl on some pages — there is no magic stealth layer. Credit math gets fuzzy on Crawl jobs because complex sites multiply page counts; estimate before launching big jobs. Extract endpoint is LLM-backed and adds external model cost on top of Firecrawl credits. Self-hosting is supported but production-grade ops (queue, headless pool) are on you.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Ingest a documentation site into a vector store via the Crawl endpoint in one job.","Add a ''paste a URL, summarise it'' feature to your product using the Scrape endpoint.","Run a daily competitive-intel pass that pulls clean Markdown from 50 competitor sites.","Wire Firecrawl into Cursor or Claude Desktop via MCP and let your assistant scrape on demand."}', 'Sweet spot: a small team that needs reliable web data inside an AI feature and explicitly does not want to own a Playwright fleet. Firecrawl''s Markdown output is the right default for RAG, and the MCP server makes it a one-line addition to any AI coding assistant.

Failure modes. Credits look generous on the marketing page but disappear quickly on real Crawl jobs over big sites — measure on a representative target before committing to a tier. Extract''s LLM cost is invisible until you read the docs carefully. For sites with serious anti-bot defenses, Firecrawl alone is not the answer — you will need a stealth proxy layer or a dedicated tool like Browser-use plus residential proxies.

What to pilot. Pick the three URLs your product actually needs, run them through Scrape and Extract on the free tier, measure output cleanliness and credit burn. If Markdown quality is acceptable and the credits-per-page rate fits your unit economics, the upgrade path is obvious; if Markdown comes back broken on your target sites, the bottleneck is the sites themselves and you should evaluate Apify or browser-use first.', now());
